('18EC32', '', 'Module 1', 'CO  1', 'KL 3', 10, 'Applying Source Transformation evaluate Vx, for the circuit shown in the figure.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/q-5.jpg" style="height:182px; width:300px" /></p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 2321, '<p>Step-1: 2 Marks</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Step-2: 2 Marks</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Step-3: 2 Marks</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Step-4: 2 Marks</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Step-5: 2 Marks</p>\r\n', '<img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/q-5%20s%281%29.jpg" style="height:447px; width:400px" /></p>\r\n', '', '', '1IA'),
('18EC32', '', 'Module 1', 'CO  1', 'KL 2', 10, '<p>Explain Electrical Circuit. What are&nbsp;the different types of Electrical Networks? Give Examples</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 2322, 'Definition: 2 Marks</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Explanation of Each network: 2m x 4= 8 Marks</p>\r\n', 'Definition of Electrical Network with example: 2 Marks</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Explanation of each Netwok 2Marks x 4 = 8 Marks</p>\r\n', '', '', '1IA'),
('18EC32', '', 'Module 1', 'CO  1', 'KL 2', 10, '<p>Explain Ideal&nbsp;and Practical&nbsp;Sources. Discuss the different types of Dependent sources with Examples.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 2323, 'Defination of Sources: 2 Marks</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Different types of Dependent Sources: 2Marks x 4 = 8 marks</p>\r\n', 'Defination of&nbsp; Ideal&nbsp;and Practical&nbsp; Sources with examples&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Different types of Dependent Sources:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>a. Voltage dependendent Volatge Source</p>\r\n\r\n<p>b. Current dependendent Volatge Source</p>\r\n\r\n<p>c.&nbsp;Voltage dependendent Current Source</p>\r\n\r\n<p>d. Current dependendent Current Source</p>\r\n', '', '', '1IA'),
('18EC32', '', 'Module 1', 'CO  1', 'KL 3', 10, 'Applying Source Transformation evaluate V<sub>AB</sub>, for the circuit shown in the figure.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0cm; margin-right:0cm"><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/q-7.jpg" style="height:349px; width:300px" /></p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 2324, '<p>Step-1: 2 Marks</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Step-2: 2 Marks</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Step-3: 2 Marks</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Step-4: 2 Marks</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Step-5: 2 Marks</p>\r\n', '<img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/q-7%20s.jpg" style="height:263px; width:400px" /></p>\r\n', '', '', '1IA'),
('18EC32', '', 'Module 1', 'CO  1', 'KL 3', 10, 'Applying Source Transformation evaluate V<sub>AB</sub>, for the circuit shown in the figure.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/q-8.jpg" style="height:167px; width:300px" /></p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 2325, 'Step-1: 2 Marks<br />\r\nStep-2: 2 Marks<br />\r\nStep-3: 2 Marks<br />\r\nStep-4: 2 Marks<br />\r\nStep-5: 2 Marks<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/q-8%20s.jpg" style="height:412px; width:400px" /></p>\r\n', '', '', '1IA'),
('18EC32', '', 'Module 1', 'CO  1', 'KL 3', 10, 'Applying Star-Delta Transformation evaluate R<sub>AB</sub>, for the circuit shown in the figure.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/q-9.jpg" style="height:128px; width:300px" /></p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 2326, 'Step-1: 2 Marks<br />\r\nStep-2: 2 Marks<br />\r\nStep-3: 2 Marks<br />\r\nStep-4: 2 Marks<br />\r\nStep-5: 2 Marks<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/q-9%20s.jpg" style="height:491px; width:500px" /></p>\r\n', '', '', '1IA'),
('18EC742', '', 'Module 1', 'CO  1', 'KL 2', 10, '<span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,&quot;sans-serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Explain the four stroke cycle of an IC Engine, with a neat diagram</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 2327, '<p>4 Strokes of an IC Engine</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;1. Intake 2. Compression 3. Power 4. Exhaust : 2&nbsp;M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Explain each stroke with diagram : 2 M&nbsp; each</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p>The 4-Stroke Cycle&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;The operation of the engine can be understood by considering the actions in any one cylinder during a complete cycle of the engine.&nbsp;One complete cycle in the 4-stroke/cycle SI engine requires two complete rotations of the crankshaft.&nbsp;As the crankshaft rotates, the piston moves up and down in the cylinder. In the two complete revolutions of the crankshaft that make up one cycle, there are four separate strokes of the piston from the top of the cylinder to the bottom or from the bottom to the top</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/Q1%283%29.jpg" style="height:346px; width:660px" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Figure illustrates the four strokes for a 4-stroke/cycle SI engine, which are called:&nbsp;<br />\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;1. Intake 2. Compression 3. Power 4. Exhaust<br />\r\nThere are two valves for each cylinder. The left valve in the drawing is called the &nbsp;intake valve &nbsp;and the right valve is called the exhaust valve.<br />\r\n&nbsp; The intake valve is normally larger than the exhaust valve.&nbsp;<br />\r\nNote that the crankshaft is assumed to be rotating in a clockwise direction.<br />\r\n<strong>Intake</strong>&nbsp;<br />\r\nDuring the intake stroke, the piston is moving from top to bottom and the intake valve is open.&nbsp;As the piston moves down, a partial vacuum is created, which draws a mixture of air and vaporized gasoline through the intake valve into the cylinder.&nbsp;The intake valve is closed after the piston reaches the bottom. This position is normally called Bottom Dead Center (BDC).</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Compression :</strong><br />\r\nDuring the compression stroke, the piston moves upward and compresses the fuel and air mixture against the cylinder head.&nbsp;When the piston is near the top of this stroke, the ignition system produces an electrical spark at the tip of the spark plug. (The top of the stroke is normally called &nbsp;Top Dead Center&mdash;TDC).&nbsp;<br />\r\nThe spark ignites the air&ndash;fuel mixture and the mixture burns quickly, causing a rapid rise in the pressure in the cylinder</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Power</strong><br />\r\n&nbsp;During the power stroke, the high pressure created by the burning mixture forces the piston downward. It is only during this stroke that actual usable power is generated by the engine.<br />\r\n<strong>Exhaust&nbsp;</strong><br />\r\nDuring the exhaust stroke, the piston is again moving upward. The exhaust valve is open and the piston forces the burned gases from the cylinder through the exhaust port into the exhaust system and out the tailpipe into the atmosphere</p>\r\n', '', '', '1IA'),
('18EC742', '', 'Module 1', 'CO  1', 'KL 2', 10, '<span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,&quot;sans-serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Briefly explain the working of spark plug with a neat diagram</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 2328, '<p>Diagram : 4 M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Working :6 M</p>\r\n', '<p>Spark Plug<br />\r\nThe spark is produced by applying a high-voltage pulse of from 20 kV to 40 kV (1 kV is 1,000 volts) between the center electrode and ground. The actual voltage required to start the arc varies with the 1. size of the gap,&nbsp;&nbsp;2.the compression ratio, and 3. the air&ndash;fuel ratio.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/Q2%282%29.jpg" style="height:398px; width:298px" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;A typical spark plug conguration is shown in Figure. The spark plug consists of a pair of electrodes, called the &nbsp;center and ground electrodes, separated by a gap.&nbsp;The gap may be 0.025 inch (0.6 mm) for one engine and 0.040 inch (1 mm) for another engine.&nbsp;The center electrode is insulated from the ground electrode and the metallic shell assembly.&nbsp;The ground electrode is at electrical ground potential because one terminal of the battery that supplies the current to generate the high-voltage pulse for the ignition system is connected to the engine block and frame.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '', '', '1IA'),
('18EC742', '', 'Module 1', 'CO  1', 'KL 3', 10, '<span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,&quot;sans-serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">With a neat diagram illustrate&nbsp;the working of a disk braking system of an automobile</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 2329, '<p>Diaagram : 5 m</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Working Principle: 5 M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<p>Drum brakes are an extension of the type of brakes used on early cars and horsedrawn wagons. Increasingly, automobile manufacturers are using disk brakes.&nbsp;<br />\r\nDisk brakes are illustrated in Figure. A at disk is attached to each wheel and rotates with it as the car moves.&nbsp;A wheel cylinder assembly (often called a caliper) is connected to the axle assembly.A pair of pistons having brake pad material are mounted in the caliper assembly and are close to the disk.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Under normal driving conditions, the pads are not in contact with the disk, and the disk is free to rotate.&nbsp;When the brake pedal is depressed, hydraulic pressure is applied through the brake uid to force the brake pads against the disk. The braking force that decelerates the car results from friction between the disk and the pads.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/Q3%281%29.jpg" style="height:280px; width:423px" /><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '', '', '1IA'),
('18EC742', '', 'Module 1', 'CO  1', 'KL 2', 10, '<span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,&quot;sans-serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Explain the significance of Ignition System in the Automobile</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 2330, '<p>Ignition System : 3 M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Significance : 7 M</p>\r\n', '<p>To produce power, the gasoline engine must not only have a correct mixture of fuel and air, but also some means of initiating combustion of the mixture.&nbsp;<br />\r\nEssentially the only practical means is with an electric spark produced across the gap between a pair of electrodes of a spark plug. The electric arc or spark provides sufcient energy to cause combustion. This phenomenon is called Ignition. Once a stable combustion has been initiated, there is no further need for the spark. Typically, the spark must persist for a period of about a millisecond.&nbsp;<br />\r\nTo produce power, the gasoline engine must not only have a correct mixture of fuel and air, but also some means of initiating combustion of the mixture.&nbsp;<br />\r\nEssentially the only practical means is with an electric spark produced across the gap between a pair of electrodes of a spark plug. The electric arc or spark provides sufcient energy to cause combustion. This phenomenon is called Ignition. Once a stable combustion has been initiated, there is no further need for the spark. Typically, the spark must persist for a period of about a millisecond.&nbsp;<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '', '', '1IA'),
('18EC742', '', 'Module 1', 'CO  1', 'KL 3', 10, '<span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,&quot;sans-serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Illustrate the working of High Voltage Circuit and distribution with neat diagram</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 2331, '<p>Diagram : 3 M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Working Principle : 3 M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Operation : 4M</p>\r\n', '<p><strong>High-Voltage Circuit and Distribution</strong>&nbsp;<br />\r\nThe ignition system provides the high-voltage pulse that initiates the arc. Figure is a schematic of the electrical circuit for the ignition system. The high-voltage pulse is generated by inductive discharge of a special high-voltage transformer commonly called an ignition coil.&nbsp;The high-voltage pulse is delivered to the appropriate spark plug at the correct time for ignition by a distribution circuit.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/Q4%281%29.jpg" style="height:546px; width:813px" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>In a modern engine, the breaker points have been replaced with an electronic control module in which a power transistor controls the coil current.&nbsp;Before the advent of modern electronic controls, the distribution of high voltage pulses was accomplished with a rotary switch called the distributor.&nbsp;The center electrode is mechanically driven by the camshaft (via gears) and rotates synchronously at camshaft speed (i.e., one-half of crankshaft speed).The distributor is an obsolete means for distribution of the spark to the appropriate spark plug, and is being replaced by multiple coils.A set of electrical leads, commonly called spark plug wires, is connected between the various spark plug center terminals and the individual terminals in the distributor cap.&nbsp;The center terminal in the distributor cap is connected to the ignition coil secondary.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '', '', '1IA'),
('18EC742', '', 'Module 1', 'CO  1', 'KL 2', 10, '<span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,&quot;sans-serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Explain briefly what motivated the use of Electronic Engine Control system in the automobile</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 2332, '<p>Motivation of Electronic Control in Automobile: 4&nbsp;M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Explanation of Each&nbsp; : 6M</p>\r\n', '<p>Engine control in the vast majority of engines means regulating fuel and air intake as well as spark timing to achieve desired performance in the form of torque or power output.&nbsp;Until the late 1960s, control of the engine output torque and RPM was accomplished through some combination of mechanical, pneumatic, or hydraulic systems. Then, in the 1970s, Electronic control systems were introduced.&nbsp;<br />\r\n<strong>MOTIVATION FOR ELECTRONIC ENGINE CONTROL&nbsp;</strong><br />\r\nThe motivation for electronic engine control came in part from two government requirements.&nbsp;<br />\r\nThe <strong>rst</strong> came about as a result of legislation to regulate automobile exhaust emissions under the authority of the Environmental Protection Agency (EPA).&nbsp;<br />\r\nThe <strong>second</strong> was a thrust to improve the national average fuel economy by government regulation.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Exhaust Emissions :</strong><br />\r\nThe engine exhaust consists of the products of combustion of the air and gasoline mixture. Gasoline is a mixture of chemical compounds that are called hydrocarbons. This name is derived from the chemical formation of the various gasoline compounds, each of which is a chemical union of hydrogen (H) and carbon (C) in various proportions. Gasoline also contains natural impurities as well as chemicals added by the rener. All of these can produce undesirable exhaust elements.&nbsp;<br />\r\nDuring the combustion process, the carbon and hydrogen combine with oxygen from the air, releasing heat energy and forming various chemical compounds. If the combustion were perfect, the exhaust gases would consist only of carbon dioxide (CO2) and water (H2O), neither of which is considered harmful to human Unfortunately, the combustion of the SI engine is not perfect. In addition to the CO2 and H2O, the exhaust contains amounts of carbonmonoxide (CO), oxides of nitrogen (chemical unions of nitrogen and oxygen that are denoted NOx), unburned hydrocarbons (HC), oxides of sulfur, and other compounds. Some of the exhaust constituents are considered harmful and have come under the control of the federal government. The exhaust emissions controlled by government standards are CO, HC, and NOx.&nbsp;<br />\r\nAutomotive exhaust emission control requirements started in the United States in 1966 when the California state regulations became effective. Since then, the federal government has imposed emission control limits for all states, and the standards became progressively tighter throughout the remainder of the twentieth century and will continue to tighten in the twenty-rst century.&nbsp;health in the atmosphere. In fact, both are present in a human&rsquo;s breath</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Auto manufacturers found that the traditional engine controls could not control the engine sufciently to meet these emission limits and maintain adequate engine performance at the same time, so they turned to electronic controls.<br />\r\n<strong>Fuel Economy</strong>&nbsp;<br />\r\nEveryone has some idea of what fuel economy means. It is related to the number of miles that can be driven for each gallon of gasoline consumed. It is referred to as miles per gallon (MPG) or simply mileage.&nbsp;Just like it improves emission control, another important feature of electronic engine control is its ability to improve fuel economy<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '', '', '1IA'),
('18EC742', '', 'Module 1', 'CO  1', 'KL 3', 10, '<span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,&quot;sans-serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Illustrate with neat diagram the principle used in steering system of an automobile</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 2333, '<p>Diagram : 4 M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Explanation : 6 M</p>\r\n', '<p><strong>STEERING SYSTEM</strong><br />\r\nA steering system is one of the major automotive subsystems required for operation of the car.&nbsp;It provides the driver control of the path of the car over the ground.&nbsp;<br />\r\nSteering functions by rotating the plane of the front wheels in the desired direction of the turn.&nbsp;The angle between the front wheel plane and the longitudinal axis of the car is known as the steering angle.&nbsp;This angle is proportional to the rotation angle of the steering wheel.<br />\r\n<img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/Q8%281%29.jpg" style="height:551px; width:813px" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Traditionally, automotive steering systems have consisted solely of mechanical means for rotating the wheels about a nominally vertical axis in response to rotation of the steering wheel.&nbsp;The inclination of this axis gives rise to a restoring torque that tends to return the wheels to planes that are parallel to the vehicle&rsquo;s longitudinal axis so that the car will tend to travel straight ahead. This restoring torque provides a steering stability for the caWhen steering the car, the driver must provide sufcient torque to overcome the restoring torque.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Because the restoring torque is proportional to the vehicle weight for any given steering angle, considerable driver effort is required for large cars, particularly at low speeds and when parking.In order to overcome this effort in relatively large cars, a power steering system is added. This system consists of an engine-driven hydraulic pump, a hydraulic actuator, and control valve. Whenever the steering wheel is turned, a proportioning valve opens, allowing hydraulic pressure to activate the actuator.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The high-pressure hydraulic uid pushes on one side of the piston.&nbsp; The piston, in turn, is connected to the steering linkage and provides mechanical torque to assist the driver in turning.&nbsp; This hydraulic force is often called steering boost.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '', '', '1IA'),
('18EC742', '', 'Module 1', 'CO  1', 'KL 3', 10, '<span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,&quot;sans-serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Illustrate the Effect of Air/Fuel Ratio and Spark Timing on the Engine Performance in the automobile</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 2334, '<p>Explanation of Effect on Air / Fuel&nbsp;Ratio on Performance : 5 M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Explanation of&nbsp;Effect on Spark Timing&nbsp;on Performance : 5 M</p>\r\n', '<p><strong>Effect of Air/Fuel Ratio on Performance</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Figure illustrates the variation in the performance variables of Torque (T) and Brake power (BSFC) as well as engine emissions with variations in the air/fuel ratio with xed spark timing and a constant engine speed.&nbsp;In this gure the exhaust gases are represented in brake-specic form. This is a standard way to characterize exhaust gases whose absolute emission levels are proportional to power.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>One specic air/fuel ratio is highly signicant in electronic fuel control systems, namely, the stoichiometric mixture. The stoichiometric (i.e., chemically correct) mixture corresponds to an air and fuel combination such that if combustion were perfect all of the hydrogen and carbon in the fuel would be converted by the burning process to H2O and CO2.&nbsp;For gasoline the stoichiometric mixture ratio is 14.7:1. Stoichiometry is sufciently important that the fuel and air mixture is often represented by a ratio called the equivalence ratio, which is given the specic designation &lambda; (i.e., the Greek letter lambda). The equivalence ratio is dened as follows:<br />\r\n<img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/Q8_1.jpg" style="height:363px; width:734px" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>A relatively low air/fuel ratio, below 14.7 (corresponding to &lambda;&lt;1), is called a rich mixture; an air/fuel ratio above 14.7 (corresponding to &lambda;&gt;1) is called a lean mixture. Emission control is strongly affected by air/fuel ratio, or by &lambda;.<br />\r\nNote from Figure that torque (T) reaches a maximum in the air/fuel ratio range of 12 to 14. The exact air/fuel ratio for which torque is maximum depends on the engine conguration, engine speed, and ignition timing.&nbsp;Also note that the CO and unburned hydrocarbons tend to decrease sharply with increasing air/fuel ratios, as one might expect because there is relatively more oxygen available for combustion with lean mixtures than with rich mixtures.&nbsp;Unfortunately for the purposes of controlling exhaust emissions, the NOx exhaust concentration increases with increasing air/fuel ratios. That is, there is no air/fuel ratio that simultaneously minimizes all regulated exhaust gases.&nbsp;<br />\r\n<strong>Effect of Spark Timing on Performance</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Spark advance is the time before top dead center (TDC) when the spark is initiated. It is usually expressed in number of degrees of crankshaft rotation relative to TDC.&nbsp;Figure reveals the inuence of spark timing on brake specic exhaust emissions with constant speed and constant air/fuel ratio. Note that both NOx and HC generally increase with increased advance of spark timing. BSFC and torque are also strongly inuenced by timing.&nbsp;Figure shows that maximum torque occurs at a particular advanced timing denoted MBT.&nbsp;Operation at or near MBT is desirable since this spark timing tends to optimize performance. This optimal spark timing varies with RPM.&nbsp;Engine control strategy involves regulating fuel delivery at a stoichiometric mixture and varying ignition timing for optimized performance.&nbsp;<br />\r\n<img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/Q8_2.jpg" style="height:345px; width:585px" /><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '', '', '1IA');
INSERT INTO `question_master2` (`course_code`, `CID`, `mo`, `co`, `kl`, `marks`, `question`, `r1`, `remarks1`, `r2`, `remarks2`, `r3`, `remarks3`, `final`, `q_id`, `question_number`, `qno`, `key1`, `scheme`, `cat2`, `ete`, `IA`) VALUES
('18EC742', '', 'Module 1', 'CO  1', 'KL 2', 10, '<span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,&quot;sans-serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Define the following terms</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">a. Power&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; b. BSFC&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;c. Torque&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;d. Volumetric Efficiency&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; e. Thermal Efficiency</span></span></p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 2335, '<p>Defination of Each :2 M ( 5 * 2 = 10 M)</p>\r\n', '<p><strong>Power</strong><br />\r\nThe most common performance rating that has been applied to automobiles is a power rating of the engine. It normally is given in kilowatts or, formerly, in horsepower (note: .746 kilowatt = 1 horsepower). Power is the rate at which the engine is doing useful work. It varies with engine speed and throttle angle. Power may be measured at the drive wheels or at the engine output shaft<br />\r\n<strong>BSFC (Brake-Specic Fuel Consumption):</strong>BSFC is a measurement of an engine&rsquo;s fuel economy. It is the ratio of fuel ow to the brake power output of the engine.<br />\r\n<strong>Torque:</strong><br />\r\nEngine torque is the twisting action produced on the crankshaft by the cylinder pressure pushing on the piston during the power stroke. Torque is produced whenever a force is applied to a lever</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Volumetric Efficiency:</strong>The variation in torque with RPM is strongly inuenced by the volumetric efciency, or &ldquo;breathing efciency.&rdquo; Volumetric Efciency actually describes how well the engine functions as an air pump, drawing air and fuel into the various cylinders.<br />\r\n&nbsp;<br />\r\n<strong>Thermal Efficiency: &nbsp;</strong> &nbsp;Thermal efciency expresses the mechanical energy that is delivered to the vehicle relative to the energy content of the fuel</p>\r\n', '', '', '1IA'),
('18EC742', '', 'Module 1', 'CO  1', 'KL 2', 10, '<span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,&quot;sans-serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Explain the Significance on Exhaust Emission which has improved the fuel efficiency of the automobile</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 2336, '<p>Explanation of Effect of Exhaust Gas Recirculation on Performance :10 M</p>\r\n', '<p><strong>Effect of &nbsp;Exhaust Gas Recirculation on Performance</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Up to this point in the discussion, only the traditional calibration parameters of the engine (air/fuel ratio and spark timing) have been considered.&nbsp;However, by adding another control variable, the undesirable exhaust gas emission of NOx can be signicantly reduced while maintaining a relatively high level of torque. This new control variable, Exhaust Gas Recirculation (EGR),consists of recirculating a precisely controlled amount of exhaust gas into the intake.&nbsp;Figure shows that exhaust gas recirculation is a major subsystem of the overall control system. Its inuence on emissions is shown in Figures 5.10 and 5.11 as a function of the percentage of exhaust gas in the intake.&nbsp;<br />\r\nFigure 5.10&nbsp;shows the dramatic reduction in NOx emission when plotted against air/fuel ratio, and&nbsp;Figure 5.11&nbsp;shows the effect on performance variables as the percentage of EGR is increased.&nbsp;<br />\r\nNote that the emission rate of NOx is most strongly inuenced by EGR and decreases as the percentage of EGR increases. The HC emission rate increases with increasing EGR; however, for relatively low EGR percentages, the HC rate changes only slightly.&nbsp;<br />\r\nThe mechanism by which EGR affects NOx production is related to the peak combustion temperature. Roughly speaking, the NOx generation rate increases with increasing peak combustion temperature if all other variables remain xed.&nbsp;Increasing EGR tends to lower this temperature; therefore, it tends to lower NOx generation</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/Q10%281%29.jpg" style="height:470px; width:960px" /><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '', '', '1IA'),
('18EC742', '', 'Module 1', 'CO  1', 'KL 2', 10, '<span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,&quot;sans-serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">With a neat diagram explain the analysis of intake manifold pressure in the automobile</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 2337, '<p>Diagram : 5 M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Working Principle : 5 M</p>\r\n', '<p>fuel control is based on a measurement of mass air ow rate and on regulation of fuel ow to maintain a desired air/fuel ratio.&nbsp;Mass air ow measurement can be accomplished either directly or indirectly via computation based on measurement of other intake variables. For an understanding of this important measurement, it is helpful to consider the characteristics of the intake system. Below figure is a very simplied sketch of an intake manifold.&nbsp;In this simplied sketch, the engine is viewed as an air pump drawing air into the intake manifold. Whenever the engine is not running, no air is being pumped and the intake MAP is at atmospheric pressure. This is the highest intake MAP for an unsupercharged engine. (A supercharged engine has an external air pump called a supercharger.)&nbsp; When the engine is running, the air ow is impeded by the partially closed throttle plate. This reduces the pressure in the intake manifold so it is lower than atmospheric pressure; therefore, a partial vacuum exists in the intake.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/Q11%281%29.jpg" style="height:313px; width:462px" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If the engine were a perfect air pump and if the throttle plate were tightly closed, a perfect vacuum could be created in the intake manifold. A perfect vacuum corresponds to zero absolute pressure. However, the engine is not a perfect pump and some air always leaks past the throttle plate. (In fact, some air must get past a closed throttle or the engine cannot idle.) Therefore, the intake MAP uctuates during the stroke of each cylinder and as pumping is switched from one cylinder to the next.<br />\r\nFor a control system application, only average manifold pressure is required. The torque produced by an engine at a constant RPM is approximately proportional to the average value of MAP.&nbsp;<br />\r\nThe rapid uctuations in instantaneous MAP are not of interest to the engine controller. Therefore, the manifold pressure measurement method should lter out the pressure uctuations at frequency fp and measure only the average pressure.&nbsp;<br />\r\nOne way to achieve this ltering is to connect the MAP sensor to the intake manifold through a very small diameter tube. The rapid uctuations in pressure do not pass through this tube, but the average pressure does. The MAP sensor output voltage then corresponds only to the average manifold pressure.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '', '', '1IA'),
('18EC742', '', 'Module 1', 'CO  1', 'KL 3', 10, '<span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,&quot;sans-serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Illustrate the working of Electronic Ignition system&nbsp; with a neat diagram of an Automobile</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 2338, '<p>Electronic Ignition : 3&nbsp;M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Diagram : 3 M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Working Principle : 4 M</p>\r\n', '<p>The torque produced by an engine at a constant RPM is approximately proportional to the average value of MAP.The engine ignition system exists solely to provide an electric spark to ignite the mixture in the cylinder. The engine performance is strongly inuenced by the spark timing relative to the engine position during the compression stroke.&nbsp;&nbsp;The spark advance (relative to TDC) is determined in the electronic engine control based on a number of measurements made by sensors.&nbsp;<br />\r\nHowever, in order to generate a spark at the correct spark advance the electronic engine control must have a measurement of the engine position.&nbsp; Engine position is determined by a sensor coupled to the camshaft or the crankshaft, or a combination of each, depending on the conguration for the electronic ignition.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Recall from Module 1 that the voltage pulse to re the spark plug in any given cylinder was routed from the coil to the relevant spark plug via a rotary switch called a distributor. In modern engines, the distributor has been replaced with multiple coils, with each coil dedicated to one or sometimes two cylinder(s).<br />\r\nElectronic ignition can be implemented as part of an integrated system or as a stand-alone ignition system. A block diagram is shown in below Figure.<br />\r\nBased on measurements from the sensors for engine position, mass air ow or manifold pressure, and RPM, the electronic controller computes the correct spark advance for each cylinder.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/Q12%281%29.jpg" style="height:323px; width:523px" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>At the appropriate time the controller sends a trigger signal to the driver circuits, thereby initiating spark. Before the spark occurs, the driver circuit sends a relatively large current through the primary (P) of the coil.<br />\r\n&nbsp;When the spark is to occur, a trigger pulse is sent to the driver circuit for the coil associated with the appropriate spark plug.<br />\r\nThis trigger causes the driver circuit to interrupt the current in the primary. A very high voltage is induced at this time in the secondary (S) of the coil. This high voltage is applied to the spark plugs, causing them to re.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '', '', '1IA'),
('18EC742', '', 'Module 1', 'CO  1', 'KL 3', 10, '<span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,&quot;sans-serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">What are the major controller inputs and outputs from/to Engine? illustrate their connection between Engine and Controller with neat diagram and explain briefly?</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 2339, '<p><br />\r\n&nbsp;major controller inputs&nbsp;to Engine : 2 M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Diagram :2 M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Explain Each : 2&nbsp;M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>outputs from/to Engine : 2 M&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Diagram :2 M</p>\r\n', '<p><strong>Inputs to Controllers&nbsp;</strong><br />\r\nFigure identied the major physical quantities that are sensed and provided to the electronic controller as inputs.<br />\r\n&nbsp;They are as follows:<br />\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;1. Throttle position sensor (TPS)&nbsp;<br />\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;2. Mass air ow rate (MAF)&nbsp;<br />\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;3. Engine temperature (coolant temperature) (CT)&nbsp;<br />\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;4. Engine speed (RPM) and angular position&nbsp;<br />\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;5. Exhaust gas recirculation (EGR) valve position&nbsp;<br />\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;6. Exhaust gas oxygen (EGO) concentration&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/Q13_1.jpg" style="height:248px; width:410px" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Outputs from Controllers&nbsp;</strong><br />\r\nFigure identied the major physical quantities that are outputs from the controller.&nbsp;<br />\r\nThese outputs are&nbsp;<br />\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 1. Fuel metering control&nbsp;<br />\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 2. Ignition control&nbsp;<br />\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 3. Ignition timing&nbsp;<br />\r\n&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 4. Exhaust gas recirculation control<br />\r\n<img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/Q13_2.jpg" style="height:254px; width:521px" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Explain Each</p>\r\n', '', '', '1IA'),
('18EC751', '', 'Module 1', 'CO  1', 'KL 3', 10, '<span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Illustrate the various mechanisms of propagation of electromagnetic waves through air.</span></span></p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 2340, '<span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Various mechanisms of propagation of electromagnetic waves</span></span></p>\r\n', '<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0">Radio waves</span><span style="color:black">, also called </span><span style="color:#0070c0">electromagnetic waves</span><span style="color:black">, can travel </span><span style="color:#0070c0">large distances, unlike sound waves or heat waves</span><span style="color:black">.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">They can also </span><span style="color:#0070c0">penetrate nonmetallic objects</span><span style="color:black">, unlike light waves.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Radio waves are </span><span style="color:#0070c0">free of some of the limitations </span><span style="color:black">that heat and light waves experience.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Heat waves and visible light waves can be seen and felt, but </span><span style="color:#0070c0">radio waves are invisible</span><span style="color:black">.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Thus, radio waves are an </span><span style="color:#0070c0">excellent means to transmit electrical signals carrying information data</span></span> <span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">without wires.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify">\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><strong>Radio Path</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12px">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;; font-size:12px"><span style="color:black">A </span><span style="color:#0070c0">radio path </span><span style="color:black">is a </span><span style="color:#0070c0">path traveled </span><span style="color:black">by the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">radio signal </span><span style="color:black">in the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">wireless medium </span><span style="color:black">from the transmitter to the receiver.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">transmission path </span><span style="color:black">between the transmitter and the receiver can vary from </span><span style="color:#0070c0">simple line-of-sight to severely obstructed </span><span style="color:black">one by natural terrain, buildings, other nearby moving vehicles, and the presence of heavy foliage (vegetation).</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Various methods of </span><span style="color:#0070c0">propagation of electromagnetic waves </span><span style="color:black">depend largely on frequency in addition to their </span><span style="color:#0070c0">own characteristics as well as environment properties</span><span style="color:black">.</span></span> </span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify">\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><strong>Ground-Wave Propagation</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">electromagnetic wave </span><span style="color:black">almost following the curvature of the earth from transmitter to receiver is known as </span><span style="color:#0070c0">ground wave propagation or surface-wave propagation.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">It is a well-known fact that the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">radio frequencies up to about 2 MHz </span><span style="color:black">induces a current in the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">earth&rsquo;s surface while propagating along the curvature of the earth.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Therefore, </span><span style="color:#0070c0">ground waves must be vertically polarized </span><span style="color:black">so to prevent short-circuiting the electric component of the electromagnetic waves.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">As the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">electromagnetic wave propagates over the earth</span><span style="color:black">, the wavefront near the earth is slowed down which causes </span><span style="color:#0070c0">attenuation of the signal strength.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Thus, the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">maximum range of a transmitter depends </span><span style="color:black">on its </span><span style="color:#0070c0">frequency</span><span style="color:black"> as well as its </span><span style="color:#0070c0">power</span><span style="color:black">.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Moreover, the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">electromagnetic waves in the frequency range </span><span style="color:black">up to 3 MHz are scattered by the atmosphere rather than penetrating through it.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">This also </span><span style="color:#0070c0">causes the waves </span><span style="color:black">to follow the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">earth&rsquo;s curvature and results in ground wave propagation.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><strong>Sky-wave Propagation</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12px">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;; font-size:12px"><span style="color:black">A radio signal from an earth-based transmitting antenna is radiated upwards in the atmosphere.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">It gets reflected back to the earth from the ionosphere through successive refractive phenomenon from different layers of the atmosphere.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The radio signals are received on the earth well beyond the horizon.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Sky-wave propagation can travel a very large distance (up to thousands of kilometers) between transmitter antenna and receiver antenna.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">It can experience a number of hops, bouncing back and forth between the ionosphere and the earth&rsquo;s surface.</span></span> </span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify">\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><strong>Space-wave propagation</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.04pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Space-wave propagation, also known as Line-Of-Sight (LOS) propagation or tropospheric waves, travel in the troposphere which is part of the atmosphere nearer to the earth&rsquo;s surface.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.04pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Troposphere is the region at about 10 km above the surface of the earth.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.04pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The temperature decays at the rate of 6.5 degree C per km till it reaches at about &ndash; 50 degree C at the upper boundary of the troposphere.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.04pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">It is useful for ground-based radio communication when the transmitter and receiver antenna must be within an effective LOS condition between them.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.04pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The microwave frequencies are refracted by the troposphere and bent along its curvature.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.04pt; text-align:justify">\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><strong>Duct Propagation </strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:4.32pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">At microwave frequencies in the range of 1000 MHz, the electromagnetic waves are neither propagated along the surface of the earth nor reflected by the ionosphere.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:4.32pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">But the long-distance (up to as large as 1000 km) propagation occurs due to the phenomenon of super refraction or duct propagation.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:4.32pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The distance of tropospheric wave propagation is much greater than the line-of-sight propagation.</span></span></span></div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n', '', '', '1IA'),
('18EC751', '', 'Module 1', 'CO  1', 'KL 4', 10, '<span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Analyze the expression for free-space propagation path-loss and derive the received signal power. Make suitable assumptions as necessary.</span></span></p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 2341, '<span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Expression for free-space propagation path-loss</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Derive the received signal power</span></span></p>\r\n', '<span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><strong>Free-Space Propagation</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:4.8pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The free-space environment could be categorized as one having less obstruction due to man-made structures such as buildings and natural hills or vegetation.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:4.8pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Free-space propagation model is the fundamental for all propagation path-loss models for any wireless communication application.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:4.8pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Free-space propagation model is used to predict the received signal strength when the transmitter and receiver has clear line-of-sight signal path between them.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:4.8pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The transmitted RF signal strength decreases with distance.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:4.8pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The radio coverage can be estimated using the transmitter power, the path-loss model and the receiver sensitivity.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:4.8pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">In free-space propagation, there is no loss of energy as radio wave propagates in free space, but there is attenuation due to the spreading of the electromagnetic waves.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:4.8pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">In most operating environments, it is observed that the radio signal strength decays as some power &gamma; of the distance, called the power-distance gradient or path-loss exponent.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:4.8pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">That is, receieved signal strength, P</span></span><sub><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">r</span></span></sub><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"> will be proportional to P</span></span><sub><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">t</span></span></sub><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"> r</span></span><sup><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">&ndash; y</span></span></sup><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">, where P<sub>t</sub> is the transmitted power and r is the distance of the receiver from a transmitter in meters.</span></span> </span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:4.8pt; text-align:justify">\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><strong>Power Density of Received Signal</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">An isotropic antenna radiates equally in all directions. Therefore, the power density is simply the transmitted power divided by the surface area of the sphere. That is,</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/Picture8.png" style="height:38px; width:138px" /> </span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">where PD is the power density in watts/m</span></span><sup><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">2</span></span></sup><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">, Pt is the transmitter power in watts, r is the distance from the transmitting antenna in meters, and 4&pi;r</span></span><sup><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">2</span></span></sup><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"> is surface area of the sphere.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Practical antennas do not radiate equally in all directions as in case of isotropic antennas. Let G</span></span><sub><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">t</span></span></sub><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"> be the transmitting antenna gain. Then, power density including transmitting antenna gain, G</span></span><sub><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">t</span></span></sub> <span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">is given by</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/Picture9.png" style="height:37px; width:154px" /></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Usually, antenna gain is specified in dBi, where the &lsquo;i&rsquo; indicates gain with respect to an isotropic radiator.</span></span> </span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify">\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><strong>Friis&rsquo; Free-space Equation</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:4.8pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">A receiving antenna absorbs some of the signal energy from radio waves that pass through it.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:4.8pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The signal energy in the radio wave is directly proportional to the area through which it passes.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:4.8pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">A receiving antenna having large area will intercept more energy than a smaller one.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:4.8pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Receiving antennas are also more efficient at absorbing signal power from some directions than from other directions.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:4.8pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">That simply means receiver antennas too have power gain.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:4.8pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The power extracted from the radio wave by a receiving antenna depends on its physical size as well as its gain.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The effective area of a receiving antenna can be defined as</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/Picture10.png" style="height:28px; width:94px" /></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">It implies that the effective area of a receiving antenna is the area from which all the power in the incident radio wave is extracted and delivered to the receiver unit.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/Picture11.png" style="height:56px; width:201px" /></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The effective area of a receiving antenna depends on its gain, Gr as well as the wavelength of the incident radio wave &lambda;c, and is given as</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/Picture12.png" style="height:31px; width:136px" /></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Therefore, the received power Pr in free space is given by</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/Picture13.png" style="height:75px; width:245px" /></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">This equation is known as <strong>Friis&rsquo; free-space equation</strong>.</span></span></span></div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n', '', '', '1IA'),
('18EC751', '', 'Module 1', 'CO  2', 'KL 4', 10, '<span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">A wireless communication transmitter has an output power of 165 watts at a carrier frequency of 325 MHz. It is connected to an antenna with a gain of 12 dBi. The receiving antenna is 15 km away and has a gain of 6 dBi. Analyze the power delivered to the receiver, considering free-space propagation. Assume that there are no other losses or mismatches in the system.</span></span></p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 2342, '<span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Analyze the power delivered to the receiver, considering free-space propagation</span></span></p>\r\n', '<img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/Capture1%281%29.JPG" style="height:236px; width:587px" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/Capture2.JPG" style="height:192px; width:540px" /></p>\r\n', '', '', '1IA');
INSERT INTO `question_master2` (`course_code`, `CID`, `mo`, `co`, `kl`, `marks`, `question`, `r1`, `remarks1`, `r2`, `remarks2`, `r3`, `remarks3`, `final`, `q_id`, `question_number`, `qno`, `key1`, `scheme`, `cat2`, `ete`, `IA`) VALUES
('18EC751', '', 'Module 2', 'CO  2', 'KL 3', 10, '<span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Illustrate the various </span></span><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">classification and source of noise in a communication system.</span></span></p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 2343, '<span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Various </span></span><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">classification and source of noise in a communication system</span></span></p>\r\n', '<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Electrical noise is defined as any </span><span style="color:#0070c0">undesirable electrical signal energy that falls within the passband</span></span> <span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">of the desired electrical signal.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Electrical noise contains a </span><span style="color:#0070c0">wide range of amplitude levels </span><span style="color:black">and frequency components that can interfere with the signal waveform.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The amplitude level of noise is </span><span style="color:#0070c0">random in nature </span><span style="color:black">and thus </span><span style="color:#0070c0">unpredictable.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The noise may arise from many sources and take many forms.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Noise can be classified based on its source of generation such as</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0"><strong>External Noise. </strong></span><span style="color:black">Noise is generated </span><span style="color:#0070c0">external</span><span style="color:black"> to the communication system.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0"><strong>Internal Noise. </strong></span><span style="color:black">Noise is created </span><span style="color:#0070c0">within</span><span style="color:black"> the communication system.</span></span> </span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/Picture14.png" style="height:337px; width:742px" /></span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify">\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; text-align:left"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0">Difference between the Noise and Distortion</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:0in; margin-top:0pt; text-align:left"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0">Noise</span><span style="color:black"> is more </span><span style="color:#0070c0">predominant</span><span style="color:black"> at </span><span style="color:#0070c0">low signal levels</span><span style="color:black">.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:0in; margin-top:0pt; text-align:left"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0">Distortion</span><span style="color:black"> assumes significance at </span><span style="color:#0070c0">high signal levels</span><span style="color:black">.</span></span> </span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:0in; margin-top:0pt; text-align:left">\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><strong>External noise</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">External noise includes </span><span style="color:#0070c0">man-made noise and natural disturbances.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><strong>Man-made Noise: </strong>The man-made noise is due to</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0">Undesired radiation pick-ups from electrical appliances </span><span style="color:black">such as automobiles, ignition, switch gears, electric motors, and aircraft ignitions</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0">Leakages from high-voltage electrical </span><span style="color:black">transmission lines, fluorescent lights, etc.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0">The man-made noise is random in nature </span><span style="color:black">and it can only be analyzed statistically.</span></span> </span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify">\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><strong>Natural Disturbances: </strong>It may be further categorized as</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><strong>Atmospheric Noise: </strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">It occurs </span><span style="color:#0070c0">irregularly</span><span style="color:black"> and is mainly caused by lightning, electrical storms, and other </span><span style="color:#0070c0">atmospheric disturbances</span><span style="color:black">. </span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">It is more severe at frequencies up to 30 MHz and thus affects both broadcast and shortwave radio frequencies.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><strong>Extraterrestrial Noise: </strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">It is also created by </span><span style="color:#0070c0">natural disturbances </span><span style="color:black">such as solar cycle and distant stars. The solar cycle disturbances are repeated every 11 years approximately, causing sunspots and corona flares. </span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">sun radiations occur over a very broad frequency spectrum</span><span style="color:black">. Similarly distant stars too radiate radio-frequency noise, called black-body noise. </span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The extraterrestrial noise affects the frequency range from about </span><span style="color:#0070c0">8 MHz to 1.43 GHz</span><span style="color:black"> approximately.</span></span> </span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify">\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><strong>Internal noise</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0">Internal noise </span><span style="color:black">is created by any of the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">passive or active devices </span><span style="color:black">used in the design of communication receivers.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Internal noise is also known as </span><span style="color:#0070c0">fluctuation noise </span><span style="color:black">because it is caused by </span><span style="color:#0070c0">spontaneous fluctuations in the physical system</span><span style="color:black">.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Some forms of internal noise occur only when there is a signal present in a circuit.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div class="O1" style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.81in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">In this case, it is known as </span><span style="color:#0070c0">nonlinear distortion </span><span style="color:black">such as harmonic and inter modulation distortion.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div class="O1" style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.81in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">It is produced by </span><span style="color:#0070c0">nonlinear amplification or/and mixing operation</span><span style="color:black"> of electronic circuits.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div class="O1" style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.81in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">It creates </span><span style="color:#0070c0">unwanted frequencies </span><span style="color:black">that interfere with the signal and degrades performance.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Other </span><span style="color:#0070c0">types of internal noise </span><span style="color:black">are </span><span style="color:#0070c0">shot noise, thermal noise, white noise</span><span style="color:black"> (means spectrum is constant irrespective of its source), partition noise, flicker noise, and high-frequency noise.</span></span> </span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify">\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><strong>Shot noise</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Shot noise is an internal noise that is generated in most of the semiconductor devices due to</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">random behaviour of charge carriers in active devices</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">random diffusion of minority carriers</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">random generation and recombination of electron-hole pairs</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">random variations in the arrival of electrons or holes at the output terminal.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify">\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:left"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><strong>Thermal noise</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Thermal noise is an </span><span style="color:#0070c0">internal noise which occurs in all electronic devices</span><span style="color:black"> (due to thermal agitation of electrons) as well as in transmission media.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div class="O1" style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.81in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">It is characterized as </span><span style="color:#0070c0">white noise </span><span style="color:black">because it is </span><span style="color:#0070c0">uniformly distribute throughout the radio communication frequency band.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div class="O1" style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.81in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">spectrum of thermal noise </span><span style="color:black">is equivalent to white noise up to a frequency of approximately 1013 Hz (the infrared region).</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div class="O1" style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.81in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">As the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">frequency increases </span><span style="color:black">further, there is a rapid exponential </span><span style="color:#0070c0">decrease in thermal noise</span><span style="color:black">.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div class="O1" style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.81in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">When thermal noise is passed through a </span><span style="color:#0070c0">narrowband filter</span><span style="color:black">, the output consists of </span><span style="color:#0070c0">narrowband thermal noise</span><span style="color:black">.</span></span></span></div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n', '', '', '1IA'),
('18EC751', '', 'Module 2', 'CO  2', 'KL 3', 10, '<span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Illustrate thermal noise and white noise also calculate the thermal noise power density at room temperature, usually specified as T = 17&deg;C or 290 K.</span></span></p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 2344, '<span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Thermal noise&nbsp;</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">White noise </span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Calculate the thermal noise power density</span></span></p>\r\n', '<span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><strong>Thermal noise</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Thermal noise is an </span><span style="color:#0070c0">internal noise which occurs in all electronic devices</span><span style="color:black"> (due to thermal agitation of electrons) as well as in transmission media.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div class="O1" style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.81in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">It is characterized as </span><span style="color:#0070c0">white noise </span><span style="color:black">because it is </span><span style="color:#0070c0">uniformly distribute throughout the radio communication frequency band.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div class="O1" style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.81in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">spectrum of thermal noise </span><span style="color:black">is equivalent to white noise up to a frequency of approximately 1013 Hz (the infrared region).</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div class="O1" style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.81in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">As the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">frequency increases </span><span style="color:black">further, there is a rapid exponential </span><span style="color:#0070c0">decrease in thermal noise</span><span style="color:black">.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div class="O1" style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.81in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">When thermal noise is passed through a </span><span style="color:#0070c0">narrowband filter</span><span style="color:black">, the output consists of </span><span style="color:#0070c0">narrowband thermal noise</span><span style="color:black">.</span></span> </span></div>\r\n\r\n<div class="O1" style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.81in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify">\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><strong>Models of a noisy resistor</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">A noisy resistor may be modeled by the Thevenin equivalent circuit which consists of a noise voltage generator in series with a noiseless resistor.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">It may also be modeled by the Norton equivalent circuit which consists of a noise current generator in parallel with a noiseless conductance (inverse of a resistance).</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The resultant motion of all the electrons gives rise to flow of current through the resistor which may cause noise.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Thermal noise power is given by</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:center"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">N = kTB</span></span> </span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">where k is Boltzmann&rsquo;s constant (= 1.38 &times; 10</span></span><sup><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">&ndash;23</span></span></sup><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"> J/K), T is the ambient temperature in degree Kelvin (K = 273 + &deg;C), B is the bandwidth of the system under consideration.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">When expressed in dBW, N = 10 log (k) + 10 log (T) + 10 log (B) dBW.</span></span> </span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify">\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><strong>Power density Spectrum of thermal noise</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The free electrons in electronic devices which contribute to thermal noise are large in number.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Assuming their random motion to be statistically independent , then the thermal noise can be Gaussian distributed with a zero mean.</span></span> </span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/Picture15.png" style="height:186px; width:427px" /></span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:left"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><strong>White noise</strong></span></span> </span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">When the thermal noise power has a uniform spectral density, it is referred to as white noise.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The adjective &lsquo;white&rsquo; is used in the same sense as it is used with white light, which contains equal amount of the whole range of frequencies within the visible band of electromagnetic transmission.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The power spectral density, S</span></span><sub><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">w</span></span></sub><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">( f ) of white noise is flat for all frequencies.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/Picture16.png" style="height:47px; width:163px" /></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">where S<sub>w</sub>( f ) is a two-sided power spectral density, No is the noise power density which is given as</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:center"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">N<sub>o</sub> = kT</span></span><sub><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">e</span></span></sub> </span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">where k is Boltzmann&rsquo;s constant and T</span></span><sub><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">e</span></span></sub><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"> is the equivalent noise temperature of the receiver.</span></span></span></div>\r\n</div>\r\n<img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/Capture3.JPG" style="height:186px; width:648px" /></div>\r\n', '', '', '1IA'),
('18EC751', '', 'Module 2', 'CO  2', 'KL 2', 10, '<span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Explain various types of analog modulation techniques. </span></span></p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 2345, '<span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Types of analog modulation&nbsp;</span></span></p>\r\n', '<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.52pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Modulation is the process of changing some characteristics of a signal, known as the carrier signal, in proportion with the instantaneous value of the modulating signal, also called as information signal or baseband signal.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.52pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Usually the frequency of modulating signal is relatively low.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.52pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The frequency of the carrier frequency is usually much greater than that of the modulating signal.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.52pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The output signal of a modulation process is known as modulated signal.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><strong>Analog modulation:</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.52pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">When the carrier signal is continuous in nature such as fixed frequency sinusoidal signal, the process of modulation for analog information signal is known as analog modulation, also known as Continuous Wave (CW) modulation.</span></span> </span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.52pt; text-align:justify">\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Types of analog-modulation techniques considering an arbitrary analog modulating signal and a fixed-frequency sinusoidal carrier signal. A typical waveform of an arbitrary analog information signal is shown in Fig.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings"><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/Picture17%281%29.png" style="height:146px; width:478px" /></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12px">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;; font-size:12px"><span style="color:black">Let the time-varying carrier signal be a high-frequency analog sinusoidal signal of the form:</span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="font-size:12px">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/Picture18%281%29.png" style="height:23px; width:181px" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Where Vc is the maximum amplitude (volts), fc is the carrier signal frequency (Hz), and q is phase angle (radians) of the carrier signal. It is obvious that amplitude, frequency, and phase are three characteristics of analog carrier signal. Accordingly, there may be three distinct possibilities for the process of analog modulation such as</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">If the amplitude (Vc ) of the carrier signal is varied in proportion to the instantaneous value of the analog information signal, the process is known as <strong>Amplitude Modulation (AM)</strong>.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">If the frequency (fc) of the carrier signal is varied in proportion to the instantaneous value of the analog information signal, the process is known as <strong>Frequency Modulation (FM).</strong></span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">If the phase angle (q) of the carrier signal is varied in proportion to the instantaneous value of the analog information signal, the process is known as <strong>Phase Modulation (PM).</strong></span></span> </span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify">\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><strong>Amplitude vs. frequency vs. phase modulation</strong></span></span> </span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Amplitude modulation is a linear modulation, whereas angle modulation (frequency and phase modulation) is a nonlinear modulation technique.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Since frequency is the rate of change of phase, frequency modulation and phase modulation are related to each other.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">In both frequency modulation and phase modulation, the angle of a carrier signal is varied in some proportion (directly in case of phase modulation; whereas the integral in case of frequency modulation) to the instantaneous value of the analog modulating signal.</span></span></span></div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n', '', '', '1IA'),
