('18EC72', '', 'Module 1', 'CO  1', 'KL 3', 10, '<span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,&quot;sans-serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">With the transfer characteristics of skewed inverter, explain the </span></span><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><span style="background-color:white"><span style="font-family:&quot;Arial&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;"><span style="color:#202124">&beta;-</span></span></span></span><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">ratio effects.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n', 'N', 'Not up to the mark', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 2490, 'T<span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">ransfer characteristics of skewed inverter and&nbsp;</span></span><span style="font-size:10.5pt"><span style="background-color:white"><span style="font-family:&quot;Arial&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;"><span style="color:#202124">&beta;-</span></span></span></span><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">ratio effects</span></span></p>\r\n', '<img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/34.jpg" style="height:223px; width:285px" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0cm; margin-right:0cm"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Fig. Transfer Characteristics of Skewed Inverters</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0cm; margin-right:0cm; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,&quot;sans-serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">We have seen that for &beta;n = &beta;p the inverter threshold voltage Vinv is V</span></span><span style="font-size:8.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">DD</span></span><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">/2. This may be</span></span><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">&nbsp;desirable because it maximizes noise margins. Inverters with different beta ratios &beta;p/&beta;n are called skewed inverters. If &beta;p/&beta;n &gt; 1, the inverter is HI-skewed. If &beta;p/&beta;n &lt; 1, the inverter is LO-skewed. If &beta;p/&beta;n = 1, the inverter has normal skew or is unskewed.A HI-skew inverter has a stronger pMOS transistor. Therefore, if the input is VDD/2, we would expect the output will be greater than VDD/2.LO-skew inverter has a weaker pMOS transistor and thus a lower switching threshold. Figure explores the impact of skewing the beta ratio on the DC transfer characteristics. As the beta ratio is changed, the switching threshold moves. However, the output voltage transition remains sharp. Gates are usually skewed by adjusting the widths of transistors while maintaining minimum length for speed.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0cm; margin-right:0cm; text-align:justify">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0cm; margin-right:0cm">&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '', '', '1IA'),
('18EC52', '', 'Module 2', 'CO  2', 'KL 2', 10, '<p>Estimate X(k), if x(n) = cosh(an), using Linearity Property.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 2491, 'Finding&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>x(n)&nbsp; &nbsp; 1 Mark</p>\r\n\r\n<p>X<sub>1</sub>(k)&nbsp; 4&nbsp; Marks</p>\r\n\r\n<p>X<sub>2</sub>(k)&nbsp; &nbsp;4 Marks</p>\r\n\r\n<p>X(k)&nbsp; 1 mark</p>\r\n', '<img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/q-9%20s%281%29.jpg" style="height:693px; width:625px" /></p>\r\n', '', '', '1IA'),
('18EC72', '', 'Module 1', 'CO  1', 'KL 2', 10, '<span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,&quot;sans-serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Explain&nbsp;</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,&quot;sans-serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">i) Operation of transmission gate and mention its advantages. -5M</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,&quot;sans-serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">ii)&nbsp; Working of tri state inverter with a neat diagram.-5M</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 2492, '<span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif">Diagram and explaination of transmission gate</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif">Working of tristate inverter</span></p>\r\n', '<span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif">i)&nbsp;<span style="font-size:11.0pt">Schematic and symbol of Transmission gate (TG)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="font-size:11.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;"><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/6.jpg" style="height:258px; width:273px" />&nbsp; <img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/5.jpg" style="height:172px; width:199px" /></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0cm; margin-right:0cm; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;"><span style="margin-left:0cm; margin-right:0cm; text-align:justify">When A is logic high both transistors are</span> ON and TG is said to be ON. When input is provided as &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;nMOS is not able to transmit strong 1, pMOS will do the function. Similarly when pMOS is not able to transmit strong 0, nMOS will do this function. Thus transmission gate is able to send both strong 0 and strong 1 without any signal degradation.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0cm; margin-right:0cm; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;"><span style="margin-left:0cm; margin-right:0cm; text-align:justify">Transmission gate </span>can be used as Multiplexing element and Analog switch</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0cm; margin-right:0cm; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">ii) Working of Tristate inverter.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0cm; margin-right:0cm; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/9%281%29.jpg" style="height:221px; width:440px" /></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0cm; margin-right:0cm; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,&quot;sans-serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">By cascading a transmission gate and an inverter forms a tristate inverter as shownin above figure.When EN = 1, EN&rsquo;= 0, thus transmission gate is ON and transmits the output Y as the compliment of inverter input A.When EN = 0 and EN&rsquo; =1, transmission gate is OFF and the output Y is in tristate or high impedance state.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0cm; margin-right:0cm">&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '', '', '1IA'),
('18EC741', '', 'Module 1', 'CO  1', 'KL 2', 10, '<span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif">a. Illustrate how the wearable devices will function with the help of IoT and what are the various applications it support.&nbsp; &nbsp; 5M</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif">b.&nbsp;What are the architectural layers in a modified OSI model for Internet of smart streetlights application?&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 5M&nbsp;</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 2493, 'a. Explanation of all applications of wearable devices&nbsp; &nbsp; 5M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>b. Explanation of all Layers&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;5M</p>\r\n', 'a.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0cm; margin-right:0cm"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Wearable devices such as watches, fitness trackers, sleep monitors and heart monitors etc. A fitness tracker wearable band has the following functions:</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:12.0pt">i. Track steps, distance, calories burned and active minutes</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:12.0pt">ii. See stats and time with a bright OLED tap display</span></span></span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:12.0pt">iii. Automatically track how long and how well you sleep and set a silent, vibrating alarm</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:12.0pt">iv. Personalize with interchangeable metal, leather and classic bands</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:12.0pt">v. Get calls, texts and calendar notifications at a glance when the phone is in a defined range</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:12.0pt">Ans b.&nbsp;</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0cm; margin-right:0cm; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Following are the layers for data interchange in the modified OSI model:</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0cm; margin-right:0cm; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">L1: It consists of smart sensing and data link circuits with each streetlight transferring the sensed data to L2.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0cm; margin-right:0cm; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">L2: It consists of a group controller which receives data of each group through Bluetooth and Zigbee, aggregates and compacts the data for communication to the Internet, and controls the group streetlights as per the program commands from a central station.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0cm; margin-right:0cm; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">L3: It communicates a network stream on the Internet to the next layer.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0cm; margin-right:0cm; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">L4: The transport layer does device identity management, identity registry and data routing to the new layer.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0cm; margin-right:0cm; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">L5: The application support layer does data managing, acquiring, organizing and analyzing,and functionalities of standard protocols such as CoAP, UDP and IP.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">L6: The application layer enables remote programming and issue of central station directions to switch on-off and commands of services to the controllers along with monitoring each group of streetlights in the whole city.</span></span></p>\r\n', '', '', '1IA'),
('18EC731', '', 'Module 1', 'CO  1', 'KL 2', 20, '&nbsp;<span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif">Explain dual computer scheme 5M</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Explain hierarchical systems 10M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 2494, 'Explanation of dual system:&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Diagram (2M)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Explanation 3 M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Explanation of hierarchical system</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Diagram (4M)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Explanation 6M</p>\r\n', 'Dual scheme system:two computers are used in controlleing a plant , as the cost of the hardware reduced&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/dual_core.png" style="height:200px; width:165px" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Hierarchical system:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>it has three levels Manager,supervisor and unit control&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/HIE.png" style="height:157px; width:200px" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '', '', '1IA'),
('18EC72', '', 'Module 1', 'CO  1', 'KL 3', 10, '<span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,&quot;sans-serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">With a neat circuit and sketch explain CMOS inverter DC characteristics by mentoring all the operating regions.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n', 'N', 'Its Mentioning not mentoring', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 2495, '<span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif">Circuit diagram of CMOS inverter.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif">Mentoring of all operating regions.</span></p>\r\n', '<img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/b.png" style="height:102px; width:139px" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Fig: CMOS inverter</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/igf.jpg" style="height:478px; width:753px" /></p>\r\n', '', '', '1IA'),
('18EC741', '', 'Module 1', 'CO  1', 'KL 3', 15, 'a. List the various functions at data-adaptation layer in a gateway of an IoT&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 5M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>b. With neat block diagram explain in detail the process of data enrichment and data consolidation at a gateway&nbsp; &nbsp; 10M</p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 2496, 'a. List of function at a gateway&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;5M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>b. Block Diagram 5M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Explanation of Data Enrichment &amp; Data Consolidation process in details 5M</p>\r\n', '<span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Ans: a. A gateway at a data-adaptation layer has several functions. These are </span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0cm; margin-right:0cm"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Data privacy</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0cm; margin-right:0cm"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Data security </span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0cm; margin-right:0cm"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Data enrichment</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0cm; margin-right:0cm"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Data consolidation </span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0cm; margin-right:0cm"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Transformation </span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0cm; margin-right:0cm"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Device management</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0cm; margin-right:0cm">Ans: b. Block Diagram</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0cm; margin-right:0cm"><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/Data%20Enrichment.jpg" style="height:540px; width:720px" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0cm; margin-right:0cm"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Following are data management and consolidation functions:</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li style="list-style-type:none"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:12.0pt">Transcoding</span></span></span></li>\r\n	<li style="list-style-type:none"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:12.0pt">Privacy,&nbsp;</span></span></span><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:12.0pt">security</span></span></span></li>\r\n	<li style="list-style-type:none"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:12.0pt">Integration</span></span></span></li>\r\n	<li style="list-style-type:none"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Compaction and Fusion</span></span></li>\r\n	<li style="list-style-type:none">Transcoding</li>\r\n	<li style="list-style-type:none">\r\n	<p style="margin-left:0cm; margin-right:0cm"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;; font-size:11pt">Means data adaptation, conversion and change of protocol, format or code using software. The gateway renders the web response and messages in formats and representations required and acceptable at an IoT device. The IoT device requests are adapted, converted and changed into required formats acceptable at the server by the transcoding software</span></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li style="list-style-type:none">\r\n	<p style="margin-left:0cm; margin-right:0cm; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Data such as patient medical data, data for supplying goods in a company from and to different locations and changes in inventories, may need privacy and protection from conscious or unconscious transfer to untrustworthy destinations using the Internet.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n	<p style="margin-left:0cm; margin-right:0cm"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Privacy is an aspect of data management and must be remembered while designing an&nbsp; application. The design should ensure privacy by ensuring that the data at the receiving end is considered anonymous from an individual or company.</span></span></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li style="list-style-type:none">\r\n	<h1 style="margin-left:5pt; margin-right:0cm"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Following are the components of the privacy model:</span></span></h1>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li style="list-style-type:none">\r\n	<h1 style="margin-left:5pt; margin-right:0cm"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:12.0pt">Devices and applications identity-management</span></span></span></h1>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li style="list-style-type:none">\r\n	<h1 style="margin-left:5pt; margin-right:0cm"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:12.0pt">Authentication,&nbsp;</span></span></span><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:12.0pt">Authorisation.&nbsp;</span></span></span><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:12.0pt">Trust,&nbsp;</span></span></span><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:12.0pt">Reputation</span></span></span></h1>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li style="list-style-type:none">\r\n	<p style="margin-left:0cm; margin-right:0cm">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n	<h1 style="margin-left:5pt; margin-right:0cm; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Secure Data Access</span></span></h1>\r\n\r\n	<p style="margin-left:0cm; margin-right:0cm"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;; font-size:11pt">Access to data needs to be secure. The design ensures the authentication of a request for data and authorization for accessing a response or service. It may also include auditing of requests and accesses of the responses for accountability</span></p>\r\n\r\n	<p style="margin-left:0cm; margin-right:0cm">&nbsp;</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n', '', '', '1IA'),
('18EC72', '', 'Module 1', 'CO  1', 'KL 2', 15, '<span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,&quot;sans-serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">&nbsp; Write a note on</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<ol style="list-style-type:lower-roman">\r\n	<li><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,&quot;sans-serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Body effect&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; -5M</span></span></span></span></li>\r\n	<li><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,&quot;sans-serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">DIBL&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; -5M</span></span></span></span></li>\r\n	<li><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,&quot;sans-serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Short channel effect&nbsp; &nbsp; -5M</span></span></span></span></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n', 'Y', 'Check KL ', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 2497, '<span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif">Explaination and equations of body effect.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif">Explaination of DIBL</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif">Short channel effect explaination</span></p>\r\n', 'i)&nbsp;<span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;; font-size:12pt">Body effect</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,&quot;sans-serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">&nbsp;MOSFETs have 4<sup>th</sup> implicit terminal called body/substrate along with gate, source&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; and drain. The threshold voltage Vt which is assumed to remain constant is no more a constant value and varies as potential between source and body is varied. This effect is called body effect.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,&quot;sans-serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;"><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/w9.png" style="height:36px; width:221px" /></span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,&quot;sans-serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">ii)&nbsp;</span></span></span></span><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,&quot;sans-serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">DIBL</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:36pt; margin-right:0cm; text-align:justify">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">As the drain voltage Vds is increased it creates an electric eld that affects the threshold voltage.This effect is called drain-induced barrier lowering (DIBL) .</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">iii) Short channel effect</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,&quot;sans-serif&quot;"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">In small transistors, source/drain depletion regions extend into the channel impacts the amount of charge required to invert the channel</span> <span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">and thus makes V<sub>t</sub> a function of channel length</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;"> . </span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Short channel effect: V<sub>t</sub> increases with L.</span></span></span></p>\r\n', '', '', '1IA'),
('18EC741', '', 'Module 1', 'CO  1', 'KL 2', 15, 'a. With neat structure explain each component of IPv4 header&nbsp; &nbsp; 5M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>b. With suitable example explain different classes&nbsp;of IP Addressing&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;5M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>c. Define HTTPS Protocol and distinguish between HTTP and HTTPS&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 5M</p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 2498, 'a. IPv4 header diagram and explanation of all fields 5M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>b. IP addressing Class A, B, C with suitable examples&nbsp; &nbsp; 5M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>c. HTTPS protocol definition and its advantages over HTTP protocol&nbsp; &nbsp;5M</p>\r\n', 'a. Header Format</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/IPv4-Frame-Format.png" style="height:421px; width:743px" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Explanation of each and every field with width of them&nbsp; &nbsp; 5M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ans b. IP Addressing range for Class A, Class B and Class C with maximum number of devices connected in each class&nbsp; &nbsp; 5M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ans c. HTTP protocol explnation</p>\r\n\r\n<p>HTTPS Protocol explanation, its advantages&nbsp; &nbsp; 5M&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '', '', '1IA'),
('18EC72', '', 'Module 1', 'CO  1', 'KL 2', 10, '<span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,&quot;sans-serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">With a neat logic diagram and waveform explain the operation of D flip-flop.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n', 'N', 'Not upto the mark', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 2499, '<span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif">Logic diagram </span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif">&nbsp;Explaination of D Flip-flop</span></p>\r\n', '<u><strong>D Flip-flop&nbsp;</strong></u></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/laksh.png" style="height:931px; width:1021px" /></p>\r\n', '', '', '1IA'),
('18EC72', '', 'Module 1', 'CO  1', 'KL 2', 10, '<span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,&quot;sans-serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">With an example explain the working of compound gates.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 2500, '<span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif">Compound gates explaination.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif">Working of compound gate with example</span></p>\r\n', '<img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/p.png" style="height:92px; width:1148px" /><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/q.png" style="height:759px; width:1093px" /></p>\r\n', '', '', '1IA'),
('18EC741', '', 'Module 2', 'CO  2', 'KL 3', 15, '<span style="font-size:12px">a. What are the Cloud Platform based different conventional methods for&nbsp;<span style="color:null"><span style="font-family:Calibri">DATA COLLECTION, STORAGE AND COMPUTING&nbsp; 6M</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>b. Define Cloud computing and briefly explain different type of Cloud Platform services&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;5M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>c. What are the cloud service models. Briefly explain&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;4M</p>\r\n', 'N', 'Check the Knowledge level', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 2501, 'a. Explanation of different conventional methods&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;6M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>b. Definition of Cloud computing and services&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;5M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>c. Explanation of cloud service models&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 4M&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Calibri"><span style="color:black"><strong>A few conventional methods for data collection and storage are as follows</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; text-align:left">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Calibri"><span style="color:black">i) Saving devices data at a local server for the device nodes. </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Calibri"><span style="color:black">ii) Communicating and saving the devices data in the files locally on removable media, such as micro SD cards and computer hard disks. </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Calibri"><span style="color:black">iii) Communicating and saving the data and results of computations in a dedicated data store or coordinating node locally. </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Calibri"><span style="color:black">iv) Communicating and saving data at a local node, which is a part of a distributed DBMS</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Calibri"><span style="color:black">v) Communicating and saving at a remote node in the distributed DBMS </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Calibri"><span style="color:black">vi) Communicating on the Internet and saving at a data store in a web or enterprise server </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Calibri"><span style="color:black">vii) Communicating on the Internet and saving at data centre for an enterprise </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="font-size:12px">Ans. c. Cloud Platform services</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Calibri"><span style="color:black">i) Infrastructure for large data storage of devices, RFIDs, industrial plant machines, automobiles and device networks </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Calibri"><span style="color:black">ii) Computing capabilities, such as analytics, IDE(Integrated Development environment) </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Calibri"><span style="color:black">iii) Collaborative computing and data store sharing </span></span></span></p>\r\n', '', '', '1IA'),
('18EC741', '', 'Module 2', 'CO  2', 'KL 2', 15, 'a. Illustrate the Data Virtualisation with suitable examples 10M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>b. What are the cloud computing features and advantages&nbsp; &nbsp;5M</p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 2502, 'Data Visualisation 10M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Cloud computing features 5M</p>\r\n', '<span style="color:null"><span style="font-size:12px">ans. a. Data Virtualisation</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:null"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Arial">&bull;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri">A characteristic of virtualized environment is that it enables applications and services to execute in an independent execution environment. </span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:null"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Arial">&bull;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri">Each one of them stores and executes in isolation on the same platform, it may actually execute or access to a set of data centers or servers or distributed services and computing systems. </span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:null"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Arial">&bull;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri">The applications or services which are hosted remotely and are accessible using the Internet can easily be deployed at a user application or service in a virtualized environment, provided the Internet or other communications are present. </span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify">\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:7.68pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:null"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Arial">&bull;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri"><strong>Virtualizations of storage </strong>means user application or service accesses physical storage using abstract database interface or file system or logical drive or disk drive, though storage may be accessible using multiple interfaces or servers </span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:7.68pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:null"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Arial">&bull;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri"><strong>Network Function Virtualization(NFV) </strong>means a user application or service accesses the resources appearing as just one network, though the network access to the resources may be through multiple resources and networks. </span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.68pt; text-align:justify">\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:7.68pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:null"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Arial">&bull;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri"><strong>Virtualization of server </strong>means user application accesses not only one server but in fact accesses multiple servers. </span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:7.68pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:null"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Arial">&bull;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri"><strong>Virtualized desktop </strong>means the user application can change and deploy multiple desktops though the access by the user is through their own computer platform (OS) that in fact may be through multiple OS and platforms or remote computers.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-top:7.68pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:null"><span style="font-size:12px">b.&nbsp;<span style="font-family:Calibri"><strong>Cloud Computing Features and Advantages </strong></span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.68pt; text-align:justify">\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><span style="color:null"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Calibri">i) On demand self-service to users for the provision of storage, computing servers, software delivery and server time </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><span style="color:null"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Calibri">ii) Resource pooling in multi-tenant model </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><span style="color:null"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Calibri">iii) Broad network accessibility in virtualized environment to heterogeneous users, clients, systems and devices </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><span style="color:null"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Calibri">iv) Elasticity </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><span style="color:null"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Calibri">v) Massive scale availability </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><span style="color:null"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Calibri">vi) Scalability </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><span style="color:null"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Calibri">vii) Maintainability </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><span style="color:null"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Calibri">viii) Homogeneity </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><span style="color:null"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Calibri">ix) Virtualilsation</span> </span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><span style="color:null"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Calibri">x) Interconnectivity platform with virtualized environment for enterprises and provisioning of in-between Service Level agreements(SLAs) </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><span style="color:null"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Calibri">xi) Resilient computing </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><span style="color:null"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Calibri">xii) Advanced security </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify"><span style="color:null"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Calibri">xiii) Low cost </span></span></span></p>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n', '', '', '1IA'),
('18EC33', '', 'Module 1', 'CO  1', 'KL 2', 10, '<span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Explain Direct &amp; Indirect Band gap semiconductor with E-K diagram?</span></span></p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 2503, 'Direct and Indirect semiconductor using E K Diagram<br />\r\n<img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/Direct%20SC.png" style="height:147px; width:300px" /></p>\r\n', '<strong>Direct Semiconductor- Explanation 5Marks</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Direct Semiconductors : Here, the minimum of the conduction band and the Maximum of valence band occur for same value of k as shown in Fig . Ex : GaAs. Thus an e- making a smallest energy transition from the conduction band to valence band without a change in k value. In the process it gives out energy. Used for LEDs, Laser.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>InDirect Semiconductor- Explanation 5Marks</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align:justify">In IndirectSemiconductors the minimum of the conduction band does not occur at the same k value as the valence band maximum , as shown in Fig 1.15. An electron promoted to the conduction band requires a change of its momentum to make the transition to the valence band (typ. occurs via lattice vibrations. Ex Si, Ge) .When an electron in the CB min. falls to an empty state in the VB max. it falls first to defect state (Et) within the band gap, giving off energy difference as heat with a change in k value and then it falls to the VB max., giving off energy difference Et as a photon of light without a change in k (or p) value. Here both momentum and Energy of e- change with Change in k.</p>\r\n', '', '', '1IA'),
('18EC36', '', 'Module 1', 'CO  1', 'KL 2', 20, '<p>a. With neat diagram explain the working principles of Power Electronics system. Illustrate the functionalities of the Power Modulator with suiatble example&nbsp; 10M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>b. With a neat circuit diagram explain the operations of Phase Controlled Rectifier. What are the applications of it&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;10M&nbsp;</p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 2504, 'a. Block Diagram 5M and explnation 5M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>b. Circuit Diagram using Diodes&nbsp; &nbsp; 3M, Explanation 4M. Applicationd of PCR&nbsp; 3M</p>\r\n', 'a. Block Diagram</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/Power%20Electronics%20Systems.jpg" style="height:373px; width:681px" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Explanation in details of PES and Modulator with suiatable examples 10M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ans. b. Circuit diagram of PCR either by HWR / FWR with Filters 3M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Explanation of Rectifier with waveforms 4M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Applications of PCR in real world 3M (Mobile Chargers, Laptop Chargers its operations)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '', '', '1IA'),
('18EC33', '', 'Module 1', 'CO  1', 'KL 2', 10, '<span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Explain the Linear Combination of Atomic Orbitals(LCAO)</span></span></p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 2505, 'Linear Combination of Atomic Orbitals(LCAO)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A linear combination of atomic orbitals or LCAO is a superposition of atomic orbitals .<br />\r\nConditions for effective linear combination of atomic orbitals:<br />\r\n&bull; The combining atomic orbitals should have same or nearly same energy<br />\r\n&bull; The atomic orbitals should have the same symmetry about the molecular axis<br />\r\nSuperposition of two orbitals are of two types :<br />\r\n1. Bonding Orbital<br />\r\nThe amplitudes of the two atomic orbitals interfere constructively with one another. So there is an enhanced amplitude between the two nuclei. As a result, any electron that occupies this molecular orbital has a high probability of being found between the two nuclei, and its energy is lower than when it is confined to either atomic orbital alone.<br />\r\n2. Anti bonding orbital<br />\r\nTaking the difference of the two atomic orbitals, however, results in destructive interference in the inter-nuclear region where the amplitude of one orbital is subtracted from the other. This destructive interference is complete on a plane midway between the nuclei, and hence there is a nodal plane&mdash;i.e., a plane of zero amplitude&mdash;between the nuclei. Any electron that occupies this orbital is excluded from the inter-nuclear region, and its energy is higher than it would be if it occupied either atomic orbital.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/LCAO.png" style="height:147px; width:300px" /></p>\r\n', '<strong>LCAO- Explanation- 5Marks</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Figure- 5 Marks</strong></p>\r\n', '', '', '1IA'),
('18EC36', '', 'Module 1', 'CO  1', 'KL 2', 15, 'a. Briefly explain various power converters with suitable circuit diagrams for each 10M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>b. What are the applications of Power Electronics in real time. Briefly explain each&nbsp; 5M&nbsp;</p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 2506, 'a. All&nbsp; types of Power Converters&nbsp; &nbsp;10M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>b. Applications of Pwoer electronics 5M</p>\r\n', 'Ans. a. Five different types of Power Convereters</p>\r\n\r\n<p>i. Phase Contriolled Rectifiers&nbsp; (PCR) using rectifiers&nbsp; &nbsp;2M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>ii. Choppers&nbsp; 2M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>iii. Invereters&nbsp; 2M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>iv. AC Voltage Regulators&nbsp; &nbsp;2M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>v. AC Cycloconverters&nbsp;2M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ans. b. Applications of Power ELectronics</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Commercial, Industrial, Domestic, Aerospace Telecommunication, Transport, utilities etc...&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;5M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '', '', '1IA'),
