('18EC751', '', 'Module 2', 'CO  2', 'KL 4', 10, '<span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">A carrier signal v<sub>c</sub>(t) = 2.8 sin (2&pi; &times; 30 &times; 106t) is amplitude modulated by a modulating sinusoidal signal v<sub>m</sub>(t) = 1.4 sin (2&pi; &times; 500t). Find amplitude modulation index, m<sub>a</sub> and percent modulation, M<sub>a</sub>. </span></span></p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 2611, '<span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Amplitude modulation index, m<sub>a</sub> and percent modulation, M<sub>a</sub>. </span></span></p>\r\n', '<p><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/Capture5.PNG" style="height:213px; width:671px" /></p>\r\n', '', '', 'IA 2'),
('18EC732', '', 'Module 2', 'CO  2', 'KL 4', 10, '<span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif">11.An antenna has a directivity of 20 and a radiation efficiency of 90%. compute the gain in dBs.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 2612, 'explaination 5 marks formula 5&nbsp;marks&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/Q11.JPG" style="height:298px; width:590px" /></p>\r\n', '', '', 'IA 2'),
('18EC751', '', 'Module 2', 'CO  2', 'KL 2', 10, '<span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Discuss the AM power distribution and limitations of AM. </span></span></p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 2613, '<span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">AM power distribution&nbsp;</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">limitations of AM</span></span></p>\r\n', '<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">For a </span><span style="color:#0070c0">single-tone sinusoidal modulating signal</span><span style="color:black">, the AM signal consists of </span><span style="color:#0070c0">three frequency components</span><span style="color:black">&mdash;the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">carrier signal </span><span style="color:black">and the two sidebands: </span><span style="color:#0070c0">upper sideband and lower sideband</span><span style="color:black">. The easiest way to compute the total average power in an AM signal is:</span></span> </span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Total power in AM signal = Carrier power + Lower-sideband power + Upper-sideband power</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:center"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">PAM = Pc + Plsb + Pusb</span></span> </span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Assuming that the AM signal appear across a load resistance RL, so that reactive volt-amperes can be ignored.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/Picture10%281%29.png" style="height:162px; width:657px" /></span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify">\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><strong>Carrier Signal Power</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">peak amplitude of the carrier term in AM signal </span><span style="color:black">is the same as that of unmodulated carrier signal. Therefore, the carrier power is given as</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; text-align:left"><span style="font-size:12px"><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/E8.png" style="height:80px; width:490px" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; text-align:left"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><strong>Lower Sideband Power</strong></span></span> </span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="font-size:12px"><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/E9.png" style="height:188px; width:581px" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="font-size:12px"><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/E10.png" style="height:287px; width:596px" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="font-size:12px"><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/E11.png" style="height:136px; width:566px" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="font-size:12px"><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/E12.png" style="height:191px; width:510px" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:red"><strong>Limitations of AM</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Amplitude modulation, or also called </span><span style="color:#0070c0">double</span></span> <span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0">sideband with carrier (DSB-C) </span><span style="color:black">(since amplitude-modulated signal has carrier-signal frequency as well as two sidebands having sum and difference of carrier and modulating frequency) has certain limitations as given below:</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0"><strong>Low transmitted power efficiency: </strong></span><span style="color:black">The useful power that lies in the sidebands is quite small as compared to the total transmitted power of the amplitude-modulated signal. So the useful transmitted power efficiency is quite low.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify">\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0"><strong>Poor reception quality: </strong></span><span style="color:black">AM broadcasting radio stations are assigned transmission bandwidth of 10KHz only so as to minimize the interference from the adjacent AM broadcasting radio stations, thereby limiting the reception quality.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0"><strong>Noisy signal reception: </strong></span><span style="color:black">An AM receiver cannot distinguish between amplitude variations that contain the desired modulating signal and that represent external noise. Therefore, the signal reception is generally noisy. AM is quite ineffective, and is vulnerable/gets easily affected by static and other forms of electrical noise.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0"><strong>Limited operating radio range: </strong></span><span style="color:black">Due to low transmitted power efficiency, signal cannot be transmitted over long distances without increasing transmitted power substantially, However, Long-range broadcast communication is possible only for short-wave AM because of wave propagation characteristics.</span></span></span></p>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n', '', '', 'IA 2'),
