('18EC36', '', 'Module 2', 'CO  2', 'KL 1', 10, 'a)&nbsp;<span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Define choppers. Explain different classifications of choppers and list out its applications in real world</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">b)&nbsp;Briefly explain performance parameters of a chopper</span></span></p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 2878, 'a) Definition of Choppers 2 Marks</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Classification of choppers 2 Marks</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Applications of Choppers 2 Marks</p>\r\n\r\n<p>b) Listing Performance parameters of the Choppers&nbsp; = 4 Marks</p>\r\n', 'a)&nbsp;A chopper is a static device which is used to obtain a&nbsp; variable dc voltage from a constant dc voltage source.<br />\r\nA chopper is also known as dc-to-dc converter.&nbsp;The thyristor converter offers greater efficiency, faster&nbsp;response, lower maintenance, smaller size and<br />\r\nsmooth control.<br />\r\nChoppers are widely used in trolley cars, battery&nbsp;operated vehicles, traction motor control, control of&nbsp;large number of dc motors, etc&hellip;..<br />\r\nThey are also used in regenerative braking of dc&nbsp;motors to return energy back to supply and also as dc&nbsp;voltage regulators.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The choppers are power circuits which obtain&nbsp;power from a fixed voltage DC supply and convert&nbsp;it into a variable DC voltage. They are also called<br />\r\nas DC choppers or DC to DC converters.&nbsp;Choppers employ forced commutation to turn off&nbsp;the thyristors.<br />\r\nDC choppers are further classified into several&nbsp;types depending on the direction of power flow&nbsp;and the type of commutation.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Choppers are of two types<br />\r\n1. Step-down choppers<br />\r\n2. Step-up choppers</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Applications:<br />\r\nSpeed control of DC motors from a DC supply&nbsp;DC drives<br />\r\nSwitch mode power supplies<br />\r\nBattery driven vehicles</p>\r\n\r\n<p>b)&nbsp;PERFORMANCE PARAMETERS</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>The thyristor requires a certain minimum time to turn&nbsp;ON and turn OFF.</li>\r\n	<li>Hence duty cycle d can be varied only between a&nbsp;minimum and a maximum value, limiting the minimum&nbsp;and maximum value of the output voltage.</li>\r\n	<li>Ripple in the load current depends inversely on the&nbsp;chopping frequency, f.</li>\r\n	<li>Therefore to reduce the load ripple current, frequency&nbsp;should be as high as possible.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', '', '', 'IA 2'),
('18EC36', '', 'Module 2', 'CO  2', 'KL 3', 10, '<span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Construct and examine the operations of the Bidirectional Controller with RL load. Draw and explain the input and output characteristics of the same</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 2879, 'Definition of Bidirectional Controllers - 2 M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Circuit Diagram and operations - 4 M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Waveforms and Explanation&nbsp;- 4 M</p>\r\n', 'In practice most of the loads are of RL type.<br />\r\nFor example if we consider a single phase full wave ac&nbsp;voltage controller controlling the speed of a single phase&nbsp;ac induction motor, the load which is the induction motor&nbsp;winding is an RL type of load, where R represents the&nbsp;motor winding resistance and L represents the motor&nbsp;winding inductance.<br />\r\nA single phase full wave ac voltage controller circuit&nbsp;(bidirectional controller) with an RL load using two&nbsp;thyristors and (two SCRs) connected in parallel is shown&nbsp;in the figure below.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/Bidirectional%20Controller.jpg" style="height:709px; width:430px" /></p>\r\n', '', '', 'IA 2'),
('18EC32', '', 'Module 3', 'CO  3', 'KL 2', 10, '<span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif">Determine the mesh currents using Mesh Current Analysis.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/q19.jpg" style="height:179px; width:300px" /></span></span></p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 2880, 'Step-1: 2 Marks<br />\r\nStep-2: 2 Marks<br />\r\nStep-3: 2 Marks<br />\r\nStep-4: 2 Marks<br />\r\nStep-5: 2 Marks<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '<img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/q19-s.jpg" style="height:532px; width:600px" /></p>\r\n', '', '', 'IA 2');
INSERT INTO `question_master2` (`course_code`, `CID`, `mo`, `co`, `kl`, `marks`, `question`, `r1`, `remarks1`, `r2`, `remarks2`, `r3`, `remarks3`, `final`, `q_id`, `question_number`, `qno`, `key1`, `scheme`, `cat2`, `ete`, `IA`) VALUES
('18EC751', '', 'Module 3', 'CO  3', 'KL 2', 10, '<span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Explain the Digital Versus analog Transmissions.</span></span></p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 2881, '<span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Digital Versus analog Transmissions</span></span></p>\r\n', '<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.52pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="color:#0070c0">Digital transmission refers to transmission of digital signals between two or more points</span><span style="color:black"> in an electronic communications system.</span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.52pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="color:black">The form of </span><span style="color:#0070c0">digital signals </span><span style="color:black">may have </span><span style="color:#0070c0">binary levels or discrete levels, or analog information signals </span><span style="color:black">converted to </span><span style="color:#0070c0">digital pulses.</span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.52pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="color:#0070c0"><strong>Analog Transmission using Baseband Channel </strong></span><span style="color:black">Figure depicts </span><span style="color:#0070c0">analog transmission using baseband channel</span><span style="color:black">, in which an </span><span style="color:#0070c0">analog information signal is sent over wireline</span> <span style="color:black">channel with </span><span style="color:#0070c0">no modulation</span><span style="color:black">.</span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.52pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="color:black">An </span><span style="color:#0070c0">example</span><span style="color:black"> of </span><span style="color:#0070c0">analog signal transmission over baseband channel </span><span style="color:black">is a </span><span style="color:#0070c0">public address system </span><span style="color:black">using </span><span style="color:#0070c0">twistedpair wire </span><span style="color:black">as a channel, and mainly comprises of </span><span style="color:#0070c0">a microphone, an audio amplifier, and a speaker</span><span style="color:black">.</span> </span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.52pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="color:black"><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/Picture11%281%29.png" style="height:74px; width:396px" /></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.52pt; text-align:justify">\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="color:#0070c0"><strong>Analog Transmission using Bandpass Channel </strong></span><span style="color:black">Figure depicts analog transmission </span><span style="color:#0070c0">using bandpass channel </span><span style="color:black">such as </span><span style="color:#0070c0">wireless channel</span><span style="color:black">, in which an </span><span style="color:#0070c0">analog information signal is sent using modulation.</span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="color:black">An </span><span style="color:#0070c0">example</span><span style="color:black"> of </span><span style="color:#0070c0">analog signal transmission </span><span style="color:black">over </span><span style="color:#0070c0">bandpass channel </span><span style="color:black">is </span><span style="color:#0070c0">broadcast radio and television systems.</span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="color:#0070c0"><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/Picture12%281%29.png" style="height:98px; width:587px" /></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify">\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="color:#0070c0"><strong>Digital Transmission over Digital Channel</strong></span> <span style="color:black">Figure depicts </span><span style="color:#0070c0">digital transmission of digital data over digital channel</span><span style="color:black">. The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">digital communication channel</span><span style="color:black"> can handle </span><span style="color:#0070c0">digital pulse signals directly after applying appropriate line encoding signaling formats.</span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="color:black">An </span><span style="color:#0070c0">example</span><span style="color:black"> of </span><span style="color:#0070c0">digital transmission over digital channel is transmission of digital data</span><span style="color:black"> such as a </span><span style="color:#0070c0">data file </span><span style="color:black">from </span><span style="color:#0070c0">PC over digital communication channel</span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="color:#0070c0"><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/Picture13%281%29.png" style="height:93px; width:493px" /></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify">\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="color:#0070c0"><strong>Digital Transmission over Analog Channel </strong></span><span style="color:black">Figure depicts </span><span style="color:#0070c0">transmission of digital data over analog</span> <span style="color:#0070c0">channel. Digital data signals or digitized analog signals are modulated onto an analog carrier signal at the transmitter end and demodulated at the receiver end.</span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="color:black">An </span><span style="color:#0070c0">example </span><span style="color:black">of </span><span style="color:#0070c0">digital transmission over analog channel include transmission of digitized speech signals over analog channels.</span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/Picture14%281%29.png" style="height:96px; width:519px" /></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="color:black">The function of </span><span style="color:#0070c0">modulation and demodulation </span><span style="color:black">is performed by a device known as </span><span style="color:#0070c0">modem.</span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify">\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:left"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><strong>Advantages of Digital Transmissions</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:left">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0"><strong>Resistant to Additive Noise </strong></span><span style="color:black">Digital communication systems are more resistant to additive noise because they use signal regeneration rather than signal amplification as in analog transmission systems.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0"><strong>Immunity to External Noise </strong></span><span style="color:black">Digital transmission signals are inherently less susceptible to interference (caused by external noise) than analog signals.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0"><strong>Ease of Multiplexing </strong></span><span style="color:black">Digital signals are better suited for processing and combining using multiplexing techniques. Even analog signals are processed using digital signal processing methods, which includes band limiting the signals with filters and amplitude equalization.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0"><strong>Convenient to Store Data </strong></span><span style="color:black">It is much convenient to store and forward digital signals. Transmission rate of digital signals can be easily varied to different operating environments and interface requirements with various types of equipments.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0"><strong>Ease of Evaluation and Measurement </strong></span><span style="color:black">The received digital pulses are evaluated during a predefined precise sample interval, and a decision is made whether the received digital pulse is above or below a specified threshold level.</span></span> </span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify">\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0"><strong>More Suitable for Processing </strong></span><span style="color:black">Digital transmission is more convenient for processing, regeneration, and amplification of digital signals. The digital signal processing includes filtering, equalizing, phase shifting, and storing of digital data.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0"><strong>Use of Signal Regenerators </strong></span><span style="color:black">Digital transmission systems use signal regeneration rather than signal amplification as in analog transmission systems. Digital regenerators sample the received noisy signals, then reproduce an entirely new digital signal with same SNR as that of original transmitted signal. So digital signals can be transmitted over much longer distances without signal deterioration.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0"><strong>Improved Performance </strong></span><span style="color:black">Digital signals can be easily measured and evaluated. It enables to compare the error performance in terms of bit-error rate (BER) of one digital system to another. Moreover, transmission errors can be accurately detected and corrected.</span></span> </span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify">\r\n<table border="1" cellspacing="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; border:1pt solid white; width:678pt">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style="background-color:#4f81bd; border-color:white; height:34.32pt; vertical-align:top; width:30pt">\r\n			<p style="margin-left:0in; text-align:left"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Arial"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:white"><strong>Sl</strong></span></span> </span></span></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style="background-color:#4f81bd; border-color:white; height:34.32pt; vertical-align:top; width:324pt">\r\n			<p style="margin-left:0in; text-align:left"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Arial"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:white"><strong>Digital transmission </strong></span></span> </span></span></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style="background-color:#4f81bd; border-color:white; height:34.32pt; vertical-align:top; width:324pt">\r\n			<p style="margin-left:0in; text-align:left"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Arial"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:white"><strong>Analog transmission</strong></span></span> </span></span></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style="background-color:#d0d8e8; border-color:white; height:89.69pt; vertical-align:top; width:30pt">\r\n			<p style="margin-left:0in; text-align:left"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Arial"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">1</span></span> </span></span></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style="background-color:#d0d8e8; border-color:white; height:89.69pt; text-align:justify; vertical-align:top; width:324pt">\r\n			<p style="margin-left:0in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Arial"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">When </span><span style="color:#0070c0">a digital data is modulated and transmitted</span><span style="color:black">, the received signals are </span><span style="color:#0070c0">far sensitive to communication channel noise</span><span style="color:black">. </span></span> </span></span></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style="background-color:#d0d8e8; border-color:white; height:89.69pt; text-align:justify; vertical-align:top; width:324pt">\r\n			<p style="margin-left:0in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Arial"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">When </span><span style="color:#0070c0">analog information is modulated and transmitted,</span></span> <span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0">less the received signals are extremely sensitive to the noisepresent in the communication channel.</span></span> </span></span></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style="background-color:#e9edf4; height:131.08pt; vertical-align:top; width:30pt">\r\n			<p style="margin-left:0in; text-align:left"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Arial"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">2</span></span> </span></span></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style="background-color:#e9edf4; height:131.08pt; text-align:justify; vertical-align:top; width:324pt">\r\n			<p style="margin-left:0in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Arial"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0">Multiplexing of several digital or digitally-encoded analog information signals </span><span style="color:black">is achieved by </span><span style="color:#0070c0">interleaving the samples of individual signals, called Time-Division Multiplexing (TDM)</span><span style="color:black">, occupying less spectrum bandwidth.</span></span> </span></span></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style="background-color:#e9edf4; height:131.08pt; text-align:justify; vertical-align:top; width:324pt">\r\n			<p style="margin-left:0in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Arial"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0">Multiplexing of many analog information signals</span><span style="color:black"> can be by </span><span style="color:#0070c0">Frequency-Division Multiplexing (FDM) which may occupy relatively larger spectrum bandwidth</span><span style="color:black">.</span></span> </span></span></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style="background-color:#d0d8e8; height:89.69pt; vertical-align:top; width:30pt">\r\n			<p style="margin-left:0in; text-align:left"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Arial"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">3</span></span> </span></span></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style="background-color:#d0d8e8; height:89.69pt; text-align:justify; vertical-align:top; width:324pt">\r\n			<p style="margin-left:0in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Arial"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0">Digital regenerators </span><span style="color:black">used along the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">transmission path recover digital data </span><span style="color:black">from </span><span style="color:#0070c0">noise, </span><span style="color:black">and then </span><span style="color:#0070c0">retransmit noise-free digital data. </span></span> </span></span></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style="background-color:#d0d8e8; height:89.69pt; text-align:justify; vertical-align:top; width:324pt">\r\n			<p style="margin-left:0in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Arial"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0">Repeaters</span><span style="color:black"> (amplifiers) used between </span><span style="color:#0070c0">transmitter and receiver </span><span style="color:black">to compensate for </span><span style="color:#0070c0">signal attenuation also amplify the accumulated noise.</span></span> </span></span></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style="background-color:#e9edf4; height:105.23pt; vertical-align:top; width:30pt">\r\n			<p style="margin-left:0in; text-align:left"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Arial"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">4</span></span> </span></span></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style="background-color:#e9edf4; height:105.23pt; text-align:justify; vertical-align:top; width:324pt">\r\n			<p style="margin-left:0in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Arial"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0">SNR of about 10&ndash;12 dB </span><span style="color:black">only is sufficient to </span><span style="color:#0070c0">recover digital data faithfully </span><span style="color:black">at the receiver. </span></span></span></span></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style="background-color:#e9edf4; height:105.23pt; text-align:justify; vertical-align:top; width:324pt">\r\n			<p style="margin-left:0in; margin-right:0in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Arial"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0">SNR of about 40&ndash;60 dB </span><span style="color:black">(not less than 30 dB in the best possible conditions) is required to </span><span style="color:#0070c0">recover acceptable analog information signal.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n', '', '', 'IA 2'),
('18EC751', '', 'Module 3', 'CO  3', 'KL 4', 10, '<span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Analyze the Sampling Theorem with proper mathematical equations. </span></span></p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 2882, '<span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Sampling Theorem with proper mathematical equations</span></span></p>\r\n', '<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">sampling theorem </span><span style="color:black">is the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">fundamental principle of digital communications. </span><span style="color:black">It </span><span style="color:#0070c0">provides the basis for transmitting analog information signal</span><span style="color:black"> by use of </span><span style="color:#0070c0">digital transmission techniques</span><span style="color:black">.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">analog information signal </span><span style="color:black">such as </span><span style="color:#0070c0">speech or video signals is sampled with a pre-determined train of narrow rectangular pulses </span><span style="color:black">in such a way so as to closely approximate the instantaneous sampling process.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">In the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">sampling process, a continuous-time varying analog signal</span><span style="color:black"> is </span><span style="color:#0070c0">converted into a discrete-time signal by measuring the signal amplitude level at periodic instants of time.</span></span> </span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify">\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><strong>Sampling Theorem for Baseband Signal</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">A </span><span style="color:#0070c0">baseband signal </span><span style="color:black">is an </span><span style="color:#0070c0">analog information signal </span><span style="color:black">which is </span><span style="color:#0070c0">band-limited having a finite energy.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0"><strong>Sampling Theorem in Time Domain</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">&ldquo;A </span><span style="color:#0070c0">baseband signal </span><span style="color:black">having </span><span style="color:#0070c0">no frequency components higher than fm Hz</span><span style="color:black"> may be </span><span style="color:#0070c0">completely recovered </span><span style="color:black">from the knowledge of its </span><span style="color:#0070c0">samples</span><span style="color:black"> taken </span><span style="color:#0070c0">at a rate of at least 2 fm samples per second</span><span style="color:black">, that is, </span><span style="color:#0070c0">sampling frequency fs &le; 2fm&rdquo;</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">minimum sampling rate fs = 2fm</span></span> <span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">samples per second is called the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">Nyquist sampling rate</span><span style="color:black">.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0"><strong>Sampling Theorem in Frequency Domain</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">&ldquo;A </span><span style="color:#0070c0">baseband signal </span><span style="color:black">having </span><span style="color:#0070c0">no frequency components higher than fm Hz </span><span style="color:black">is completely </span><span style="color:#0070c0">described by its sample values at uniform intervals less than or equal </span><span style="color:black">to 1/(2fm) seconds apart, that is, the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">sampling interval </span><span style="color:black">Ts &le; 1/(2fm) seconds.&rdquo;</span></span> </span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify">\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Then these </span><span style="color:#0070c0">samples uniquely determine the analog information signal,</span><span style="color:black"> and the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">analog signal </span><span style="color:black">may be </span><span style="color:#0070c0">reconstructed from these samples with no distortion</span><span style="color:black">.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">maximum sampling interval </span><span style="color:black">Ts = 1/(2fm) seconds is called </span><span style="color:#0070c0">Nyquist sampling interval</span><span style="color:black">.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:justify">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0"><strong>Significance of Nyquist sampling theorem</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">Nyquist sampling theorem </span><span style="color:black">establishes the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">minimum sampling rate (fs)</span><span style="color:black"> that must be used to </span><span style="color:#0070c0">transmit analog signal </span><span style="color:black">in a given </span><span style="color:#0070c0">digital communication system.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">As per </span><span style="color:#0070c0">Nyquist criterion</span><span style="color:black">, the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">minimum sampling rate must be equal to twice the highest frequency present </span><span style="color:black">in the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">input analog signal in order to ensure reliable reconstruction of the information signal at the receiver.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Thus, </span><span style="color:#0070c0">Nyquist criterion </span><span style="color:black">is just a </span><span style="color:#0070c0">theoretically sufficient condition </span><span style="color:black">which may </span><span style="color:#0070c0">allow an analog signal </span><span style="color:black">to be </span><span style="color:#0070c0">reconstructed completely </span><span style="color:black">from a set of </span><span style="color:#0070c0">uniformly spaced discrete-time samples.</span></span> </span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify">\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><strong>Proof of sampling theorem for baseband signal </strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.4pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Theoretically, a </span><span style="color:#0070c0">band-limited signal has zero value of Fourier transform beyond the highest spectral frequency fm Hz.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.4pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Theoretically, the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">Fourier transform of a band-limited signal </span><span style="color:black">extends from </span><span style="color:#0070c0">&ndash; &infin; to + &infin; </span><span style="color:black">.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.4pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">But practically the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">Fourier transform provides </span><span style="color:black">a </span><span style="color:#0070c0">finite bandwidth because higher-order</span><span style="color:black"> terms can be </span><span style="color:#0070c0">neglected without any significant error.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.4pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The statement of </span><span style="color:#0070c0">sampling theorem </span><span style="color:black">for </span><span style="color:#0070c0">baseband signal </span><span style="color:black">can be proved using the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">frequency convolutional property of the Fourier transform</span><span style="color:black">.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.4pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Consider a </span><span style="color:#0070c0">band-limited signal</span><span style="color:black">, having </span><span style="color:#0070c0">no frequency components beyond fm Hz,</span><span style="color:black"> that is, s(t) = 0 outside the frequency range (&ndash; fm &lt; f &lt; fm).</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.4pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">In frequency domain, </span><span style="color:#0070c0">this can be represented as S( f ) = 0; for | f | &gt; fm.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.4pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">sampling of band-limited signal</span><span style="color:black">, s(t) may be viewed as the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">multiplication of s(t) with a periodic train of unit impulse function s&delta;(t), </span><span style="color:black">defined as</span></span> </span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.4pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/E13.png" style="height:74px; width:478px" /></span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.4pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/E14.png" style="height:144px; width:432px" /></span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.4pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&sect;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">This indicates that the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">Fourier transform of an impulse train is another impulse train</span><span style="color:black">, but the values of the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">periods of the two impulse trains are reciprocal of each other.</span></span> </span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.4pt; text-align:justify">\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">output signal </span><span style="color:black">so(t) is a </span><span style="color:#0070c0">sequence of impulses </span><span style="color:black">located at </span><span style="color:#0070c0">uniform intervals of Ts seconds</span><span style="color:black">, having </span><span style="color:#0070c0">amplitude levels equal </span><span style="color:black">to that of </span><span style="color:#0070c0">input signal </span><span style="color:black">s(t) at the corresponding instants. That is,</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/E15.png" style="height:41px; width:277px" /></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Using the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">frequency convolutional property </span><span style="color:black">of the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">Fourier transform, the time-domain product </span><span style="color:black">of so(t) can be transformed to the frequency-domain convolution.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">convolution</span><span style="color:black"> of any </span><span style="color:#0070c0">function </span><span style="color:black">with an </span><span style="color:#0070c0">impulse function simply shifts that function</span><span style="color:black">, that is,</span></span> </span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/E16.png" style="height:123px; width:343px" /></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify">\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Arial">&bull;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0">Figure</span><span style="color:black"> depicts the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">corresponding waveforms </span><span style="color:black">in </span><span style="color:#0070c0">time domain </span><span style="color:black">as well as in </span><span style="color:#0070c0">frequency domain </span><span style="color:black">of </span><span style="color:#0070c0">sampling theorem </span><span style="color:black">using the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">frequency convolution property of the Fourier transform.</span></span> </span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/Picture15%281%29.png" style="height:318px; width:473px" /></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify">\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.68pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Arial">&bull;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">It is evident that S( f ) will </span><span style="color:#0070c0">repeat periodically without overlapping, provided </span><span style="color:black">fs &ge; 2fm</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.68pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/E17.png" style="height:45px; width:68px" /></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.68pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Arial">&bull;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">where Ts is the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">uniform sampling interval</span><span style="color:black">.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.68pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/E18.png" style="height:53px; width:80px" /></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.68pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Arial">&bull;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0">Sampling rate or sampling frequency </span><span style="color:black">fs ( = 1/Ts) should </span><span style="color:#0070c0">meet the condition </span><span style="color:black">fs &ge; = 2fm samples/second with </span><span style="color:#0070c0">minimum sampling rate </span><span style="color:black">fs = 2fm samples/sec.</span></span></span></div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n', '', '', 'IA 2');
INSERT INTO `question_master2` (`course_code`, `CID`, `mo`, `co`, `kl`, `marks`, `question`, `r1`, `remarks1`, `r2`, `remarks2`, `r3`, `remarks3`, `final`, `q_id`, `question_number`, `qno`, `key1`, `scheme`, `cat2`, `ete`, `IA`) VALUES
('18EC751', '', 'Module 3', 'CO  3', 'KL 2', 10, '<span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Explain the phenomenon of Aliasing and how aliasing can be overcome.</span></span></p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 2883, '<span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Phenomenon of Aliasing </span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">How aliasing can be overcome</span></span></p>\r\n', '<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The phenomenon of the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">presence of high-frequency component in the spectrum of the original analog signal is called aliasing or simply foldover.</span></span> </span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">When aliasing occurs, some </span><span style="color:#0070c0">desirable information </span><span style="color:black">content is </span><span style="color:#0070c0">inevitably lost in the sampling process.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Describing the phenomenon of aliasing with the help of waveforms.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Consider an </span><span style="color:#0070c0">analog signal </span><span style="color:black">s(t) whose </span><span style="color:#0070c0">spectrum</span><span style="color:black"> S( f ) </span><span style="color:#0070c0">decreases with increasing frequency without limit.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">spectrum</span><span style="color:black"> S&delta; ( f ) of the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">discrete-time signal </span><span style="color:black">s&delta; (t), resulting from the use of </span><span style="color:#0070c0">ideal sampling</span><span style="color:black">, is the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">sum</span><span style="color:black"> of S( f ) and an </span><span style="color:#0070c0">infinite number of frequency shifted replicas </span><span style="color:black">of it of the form of S&delta; ( f )</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/E19.png" style="height:42px; width:145px" /></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">replicas of S( f ) </span><span style="color:black">are </span><span style="color:#0070c0">shifted in frequency </span><span style="color:black">by </span><span style="color:#0070c0">multiples of the sampling rate fs.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Figure shows the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">spectrum of a finite-energy analog signal before sampling and composition of spectrum of discrete-time signal after sampling for two replicas of S( f ) </span><span style="color:black">at fs and &ndash; fs.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/Picture16%281%29.png" style="height:337px; width:420px" /></span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify">\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The use of a </span><span style="color:#0070c0">low-pass reconstruction filter</span><span style="color:black">, with its </span><span style="color:#0070c0">pass-band extending </span><span style="color:black">from &ndash; fs/2 to + fs/2, where fs is the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">sampled frequency</span><span style="color:black">, does not yield an </span><span style="color:#0070c0">undistorted version of the original analog information signal.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">It results into the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">portions of the frequency-shifted replicas folded </span><span style="color:black">over into the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">desired frequency spectrum.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:justify">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><strong>Aliasing Distortion</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">absolute error between the original analog signal and the signal reconstructed </span><span style="color:black">from the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">sequence obtained by sampling is termed as aliasing distortion or foldover distortion,</span><span style="color:black"> or simply aliasing error.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">If fs &lt; 2 fm, </span><span style="color:#0070c0">aliasing distortion </span><span style="color:black">will occur.</span></span> </span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Figure shows an </span><span style="color:#0070c0">illustration of aliasing distortion</span><span style="color:black">.</span></span> </span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/Picture17%282%29.png" style="height:264px; width:494px" /></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify">\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">If fs = 2fm, the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">resultant sampled signal </span><span style="color:black">is just on the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">edge of aliasing</span><span style="color:black">. In order to </span><span style="color:#0070c0">separate the signals sufficiently apart, the sampling frequency fs should be greater than 2 fm</span><span style="color:black">, as stated by the sampling theorem.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">If </span><span style="color:#0070c0">aliasing does take place</span><span style="color:black">, the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">interfering frequency component, called as aliasing frequency, will be at a frequency</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:center"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">fa = fs &ndash; fm</span></span> </span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span> </span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">where </span><span style="color:#0070c0">fa is the frequency component </span><span style="color:black">of the aliasing distortion (Hz), </span><span style="color:#0070c0">fs is the minimum Nyquist sampling rate</span><span style="color:black"> (Hz), </span><span style="color:#0070c0">fm is the maximum analog input </span><span style="color:black">(baseband or modulating) frequency (Hz).</span></span> </span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify">\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0"><strong>How can aliasing be overcome</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.52pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Arial">&bull;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">There are certain </span><span style="color:#0070c0">corrective measures </span><span style="color:black">for </span><span style="color:#0070c0">sampling of an analog information signal</span><span style="color:black"> in order to </span><span style="color:#0070c0">overcome the practical difficulties encountered in sampling and recovery process.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.52pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Arial">&bull;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">A </span><span style="color:#0070c0">practical procedure </span><span style="color:black">for the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">sampling of an analog signal </span><span style="color:black">whose </span><span style="color:#0070c0">frequency spectrum </span><span style="color:black">is </span><span style="color:#0070c0">not strictly band-limited </span><span style="color:black">involves the use of the following </span><span style="color:#0070c0">corrective measures</span><span style="color:black">:</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.52pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Arial">&bull;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Prior to sampling<strong>, </strong></span><span style="color:#0070c0"><strong>a low-pass pre-alias filter </strong></span><span style="color:black">of sufficient higher order is </span><span style="color:#0070c0">recommended to be used</span><span style="color:black">. This will </span><span style="color:#0070c0">attenuate those high-frequency spectral components </span><span style="color:black">of the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">analog information signal </span><span style="color:black">that do not contribute significantly to the information content of the analog signal.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.52pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Arial">&bull;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">filtered analog information signal </span><span style="color:black">(by pre-alias filter) is recommended to be </span><span style="color:#0070c0">sampled at a rate <strong>slightly higher </strong>than that determined by the Nyquist rate</span><span style="color:black">, that is, </span><span style="color:#0070c0">greater than 2fm</span></span> <span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Hz where fm Hz is the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">3 dB high cut-off frequency of the pre-alias filter</span><span style="color:black">.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.52pt; text-align:justify">\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.24pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">With such a </span><span style="color:#0070c0">sampling rate</span><span style="color:black">, there are </span><span style="color:#0070c0">gaps each of width </span><span style="color:black">(fs &ndash; 2fm) Hz between the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">frequency-shifted replicas </span><span style="color:black">of the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">analog signal.</span><span style="color:black"> These </span><span style="color:#0070c0">frequency gaps </span><span style="color:black">are generally refereed as </span><span style="color:#0070c0">guard bands.</span></span> </span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.24pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">In practice, a </span><span style="color:#0070c0">low-pass filter </span><span style="color:black">(pre-alias filter) is </span><span style="color:#0070c0">used at the front end of the impulse modulator </span><span style="color:black">(used for sampling). This enables to exclude the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">frequency components greater </span><span style="color:black">than the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">required maximum frequency component </span><span style="color:black">of the information signal.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.24pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Thus, the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">application of sampling process </span><span style="color:black">allows the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">reduction of continuously varying information waveform </span><span style="color:black">to a </span><span style="color:#0070c0">finite limited number of discrete levels in a unit time interval</span><span style="color:black">.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.24pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Figure shows the use of </span><span style="color:#0070c0">pre-alias filter to minimize aliasing distortion.</span></span> </span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.24pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/Picture18%282%29.png" style="height:231px; width:460px" /></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.24pt; text-align:justify">\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.24pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Accordingly, the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">reconstruction filter at the receiver end is designed to satisfy the following characteristics</span><span style="color:black">:</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div class="O1" style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.81in; margin-top:6.24pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">passband</span></span> <span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">of the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">reconstruction filter </span><span style="color:black">should </span><span style="color:#0070c0">extend from zero to fm Hz.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div class="O1" style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.81in; margin-top:6.24pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">amplitude response </span><span style="color:black">of the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">reconstruction filter</span></span> <span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0">rolls off gradually from W Hz to ( fs &ndash; 2 fm) Hz</span><span style="color:black">.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div class="O1" style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.81in; margin-top:6.24pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">guard band has a width equal </span><span style="color:black">to ( fs &ndash; 2 fm) Hz </span><span style="color:#0070c0">which is nonzero for ( fs &gt; 2 fm) Hz.</span></span></span></div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n', '', '', 'IA 2'),
('18EC751', '', 'Module 3', 'CO  3', 'KL 3', 10, '<span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Classify the various pulse modulation techniques. </span></span></p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 2884, '<span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Various pulse modulation techniques</span></span></p>\r\n', '<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">An </span><span style="color:#0070c0">analog signal </span><span style="color:black">can be </span><span style="color:#0070c0">transmitted using digital-processing techniques </span><span style="color:black">depending upon the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">nature of transmitting medium </span><span style="color:black">such as</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div class="O1" style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.81in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0">Analog communication channel</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div class="O1" style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.81in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0">Digital communication channel</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0"><strong>Analog communication channel</strong></span></span> <span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">cannot </span><span style="color:#0070c0">carry digital pulses</span><span style="color:black">, so there is </span><span style="color:#0070c0">a need of modulation and</span></span> <span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0">demodulation </span><span style="color:black">(modem) </span><span style="color:#0070c0">after digitization process.</span><span style="color:black"> This is depicted in Figure.</span></span> </span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/Picture19%282%29.png" style="height:230px; width:471px" /></span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0"><strong>Digital communication channel</strong></span></span> <span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">can </span><span style="color:#0070c0">carry digital pulses, so the digitized analog signal </span><span style="color:black">can </span><span style="color:#0070c0">be directly transmitted digitally. </span><span style="color:black">Figure shows such an arrangement</span></span> </span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/Picture20.png" style="height:202px; width:333px" /></span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify">\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><strong>Pulse Modulation</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">When any </span><span style="color:#0070c0">one characteristics </span><span style="color:black">(such as</span></span> <span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">amplitude, width or position) of a </span><span style="color:#0070c0">relatively higher</span></span> <span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0">frequency</span></span> <span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0">carrier signal </span><span style="color:black">comprising of </span><span style="color:#0070c0">discrete pulses</span></span> <span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">is varied in </span><span style="color:#0070c0">accordance with the amplitude of the analog</span></span> <span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0">modulating signal</span><span style="color:black">, it is called </span><span style="color:#0070c0">pulse modulation.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">To</span></span> <span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">transmit</span></span> <span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">an</span></span> <span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0">analog</span></span> <span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0">information</span></span> <span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0">data</span></span> <span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">using</span></span> <span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0">digital signals and digital-transmission techniques, pulse modulation </span><span style="color:black">is necessary.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0">Pulse modulation </span><span style="color:black">essentially consists of </span><span style="color:#0070c0">sampling analog information data</span><span style="color:black"> at </span><span style="color:#0070c0">regular intervals</span></span> <span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">and then </span><span style="color:#0070c0">converting those samples into discrete pulses.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">These </span><span style="color:#0070c0">pulses </span><span style="color:black">can then be </span><span style="color:#0070c0">transmitted</span><span style="color:black"> from a </span><span style="color:#0070c0">source</span><span style="color:black"> to a </span><span style="color:#0070c0">destination </span><span style="color:black">over a physical communication channel.</span></span> </span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify">\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:left"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><strong>How is </strong></span><span style="color:#0070c0"><strong>pulse modulation </strong></span><span style="color:black"><strong>different from </strong></span><span style="color:#0070c0"><strong>analog modulation</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:left"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">In </span><span style="color:#0070c0">pulse modulation</span><span style="color:black">, the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">carrier signal </span><span style="color:black">is a </span><span style="color:#0070c0">sequence of discrete pulse </span><span style="color:black">rather than a </span><span style="color:#0070c0">sinusoidal carrier signal as in analog modulation.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:left"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">type of information </span><span style="color:black">in </span><span style="color:#0070c0">pulse modulation </span><span style="color:black">as well as </span><span style="color:#0070c0">analog modulation is analog in nature.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:left"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><strong>Classification of Pulse Modulation</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:left"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Broadly, </span><span style="color:#0070c0">pulse- modulation techniques </span><span style="color:black">can be classified as:</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div class="O1" style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.81in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:left"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0">Analog Pulse Modulation</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div class="O1" style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.81in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:left"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0">Digital Pulse Modulation</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:left"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0">Analog Pulse Modulation: </span><span style="color:black">When </span><span style="color:#0070c0">amplitude or time </span><span style="color:black">of the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">carrier pulse train is varied </span><span style="color:black">in proportion to the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">instantaneous value of the analog modulating signal</span><span style="color:black">, it is know as Analog Pulse Modulation.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:left"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0">Digital Pulse Modulation: </span><span style="color:black">When the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">analog modulating signal is converted to discrete signal </span><span style="color:black">by varying the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">amplitude of the carrier pulse train </span><span style="color:black">followed by representation of discrete levels by </span><span style="color:#0070c0">digital codes</span><span style="color:black">, it is know as Digital Pulse Modulation.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:left">&nbsp;</div>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Figure shows the</span></span> <span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0">Classification of Pulse Modulation</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="font-size:25.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0"><span style="font-size:12px"><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/Picture21.png" style="height:381px; width:454px" /></span></span></span></span></p>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify">&nbsp;</div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify">&nbsp;</div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify">&nbsp;</div>\r\n', '', '', 'IA 2');
INSERT INTO `question_master2` (`course_code`, `CID`, `mo`, `co`, `kl`, `marks`, `question`, `r1`, `remarks1`, `r2`, `remarks2`, `r3`, `remarks3`, `final`, `q_id`, `question_number`, `qno`, `key1`, `scheme`, `cat2`, `ete`, `IA`) VALUES
('18EC751', '', 'Module 3', 'CO  3', 'KL 4', 10, '<span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Analyse the working of Pulse Amplitude Modulation (PAM) with block diagram. </span></span></p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 2885, '<span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Working of Pulse Amplitude Modulation (PAM)&nbsp;</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Block diagram. </span></span></p>\r\n', '<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">When the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">amplitude of a relatively higher- frequency carrier signal comprising of discrete pulse is varied </span><span style="color:black">in accordance with the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">amplitude of the analog modulating signal</span><span style="color:black">, it is called </span><span style="color:#0070c0">Pulse Amplitude Modulation </span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The PAM technique is illustrated in Figure </span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">From the figure the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">amplitude </span><span style="color:black">of a </span><span style="color:#0070c0">pulse coincides </span><span style="color:black">with the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">amplitude of the analog information signal</span><span style="color:black">. PAM waveform resembles the original analog signal depending on the frequency of the pulse carrier signal.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span> <span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0">In single-polarity PAM</span><span style="color:black">, a </span><span style="color:#0070c0">fixed dc level is added </span><span style="color:black">to the information analog signal which ensures that the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">pulses are always positive.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">In </span><span style="color:#0070c0">double-polarity PAM,</span><span style="color:black"> the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">sampled pulses </span><span style="color:black">are </span><span style="color:#0070c0">positive</span><span style="color:black"> when the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">information analog signal has positive amplitude</span><span style="color:black">, and it is </span><span style="color:#0070c0">negative</span><span style="color:black"> when the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">information analog signal has negative amplitude.</span></span> </span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0"><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/Picture22.png" style="height:453px; width:531px" /></span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify">\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><strong>Methods of Sampling</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">There are </span><span style="color:#0070c0">three distinct methods </span><span style="color:black">of sampling in PAM:</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0">Ideal sampling</span><span style="color:black">&mdash;an impulse at each sampling instant</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0">Natural sampling</span><span style="color:black">&mdash;a pulse of short width with varying amplitude</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0">Flat-top sampling</span><span style="color:black">&mdash;sample and hold (like natural sampling) but with fixed amplitude value</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Figure shows the waveform for ideal sampling.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">In </span><span style="color:#0070c0">ideal sampling</span><span style="color:black">, an </span><span style="color:#0070c0">arbitrary analog signal </span><span style="color:black">is </span><span style="color:#0070c0">sampled</span><span style="color:black"> by a </span><span style="color:#0070c0">train of impulses at uniform intervals</span><span style="color:black">, Ts. An impulse (having virtually no pulse width) is generated at each instant of sampling.</span></span> </span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/Picture23.png" style="height:166px; width:340px" /></span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify">\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><strong>Natural sampling</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0">Natural sampling </span><span style="color:black">refers to </span><span style="color:#0070c0">PAM signals </span><span style="color:black">when </span><span style="color:#0070c0">tops of the sampled pulse retain </span><span style="color:black">their </span><span style="color:#0070c0">natural shape during the sample interval.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Figure shows the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">waveform for natural sampling</span><span style="color:black">.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">In </span><span style="color:#0070c0">natural sampling</span><span style="color:black">, an arbitrary </span><span style="color:#0070c0">analog signal </span><span style="color:black">is </span><span style="color:#0070c0">sampled by a train </span><span style="color:black">of </span><span style="color:#0070c0">pulses having finite short pulse width </span><span style="color:black">occurring at </span><span style="color:#0070c0">uniform intervals</span><span style="color:black">. The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">amplitude of each rectangular pulse </span><span style="color:black">follows the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">value of the analog information signal </span><span style="color:black">for duration of the pulse.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><strong>Disadvantage</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">It is </span><span style="color:#0070c0">difficult for an analog-to-digital converter </span><span style="color:black">to convert the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">natural sample to a digital code.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">In fact, the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">output of analog-to-digital converter </span><span style="color:black">would </span><span style="color:#0070c0">continuously try to follow the changes in amplitude levels </span><span style="color:black">and may </span><span style="color:#0070c0">never stabilize on any code.</span></span> </span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0"><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/Picture24.png" style="height:145px; width:290px" /></span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify">\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><strong>Flat-top sampling</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0">Flat-top sampling </span><span style="color:black">refers to </span><span style="color:#0070c0">PAM signals </span><span style="color:black">when the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">tops of the sampled pulse remain constant</span><span style="color:black"> during the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">sample interval</span><span style="color:black">.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Figure shows the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">waveform for flat-top sampling</span><span style="color:black">.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">In </span><span style="color:#0070c0">flat-top sampling</span><span style="color:black">, an </span><span style="color:#0070c0">arbitrary analog signal </span><span style="color:black">is </span><span style="color:#0070c0">sampled by a train of pulses</span><span style="color:black"> having </span><span style="color:#0070c0">finite short pulse width </span><span style="color:black">occurring at </span><span style="color:#0070c0">uniform intervals.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0">Amplitude of each rectangular pulse </span><span style="color:black">is retained as the value of the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">analog information signal </span><span style="color:black">at the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">leading edge of the pulse</span><span style="color:black">.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><strong>Disadvantage</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Use of </span><span style="color:#0070c0">flat-top PAM samples </span><span style="color:black">results into </span><span style="color:#0070c0">amplitude distortion</span><span style="color:black">.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">There is </span><span style="color:#0070c0">delay by Tb /2, </span><span style="color:black">where </span><span style="color:#0070c0">Tb is the width of the pulse</span><span style="color:black">, that results into </span><span style="color:#0070c0">lengthening of the samples during transmission</span><span style="color:black">.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">At the receiver, </span><span style="color:#0070c0">amplitude distortion </span><span style="color:black">as well as </span><span style="color:#0070c0">delaycauses errors in decoded data.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0"><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/Picture25.png" style="height:121px; width:246px" /></span></span> </span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify">\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><strong>Aperture Effect</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">In </span><span style="color:#0070c0">flat-top PAM signals</span><span style="color:black">, the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">high-frequency contents </span><span style="color:black">of the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">analog signal are lost </span><span style="color:black">which </span><span style="color:#0070c0">results into distortion known as the aperture effect.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">aperture effect occurs in flat-top sampling</span><span style="color:black">. It is </span><span style="color:#0070c0">due to the presence of finite pulse width</span><span style="color:black"> at the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">instant of sampling in pulse-amplitude a modulated signal.</span><span style="color:black"> In fact, the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">sampling process in flat-top sampling </span><span style="color:black">introduces </span><span style="color:#0070c0">aperture error </span><span style="color:black">because </span><span style="color:#0070c0">amplitudes of analog signal changes during the sample pulse width.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:.01in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><strong>How can </strong></span><span style="color:#0070c0"><strong>aperture effect be compensated </strong></span><span style="color:black"><strong>at PAM receiver</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">This </span><span style="color:#0070c0">distortion due to aperture effect </span><span style="color:black">can be </span><span style="color:#0070c0">minimized by passing the demodulated signal through an equalizer.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">equalizer has the effect of compensating </span><span style="color:black">for the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">aperture effect.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">amount of equalization </span><span style="color:black">required in </span><span style="color:#0070c0">practical applications is usually small.</span></span> </span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify">\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:left"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><strong>Generation and Demodulation of PAM Signals</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:4.8pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Figure gives a </span><span style="color:#0070c0">conceptual block schematic of generating PAM signal</span><span style="color:black">.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:4.8pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">An </span><span style="color:#0070c0">analog information </span><span style="color:black">signal is </span><span style="color:#0070c0">passed through low-pass filter </span><span style="color:black">which </span><span style="color:#0070c0">removes any high-frequency components present in it.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:4.8pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">sampling circuit </span><span style="color:black">also </span><span style="color:#0070c0">receives a train of pulses </span><span style="color:black">from </span><span style="color:#0070c0">pulse-sequence generator.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The output is </span><span style="color:#0070c0">pulse amplitude signal.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="font-size:12px"><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/Picture26.png" style="height:227px; width:493px" /></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.68pt; text-align:left"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Figure depicts the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">process of reconstruction of desired analog signal from samples.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.68pt; text-align:left"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">At the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">receiver, </span><span style="color:black">the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">original analog information signal </span><span style="color:black">can be </span><span style="color:#0070c0">recovered using a low-pass filter</span><span style="color:black">, also called </span><span style="color:#0070c0">reconstruction filter.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.68pt; text-align:left"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">resultant output waveform </span><span style="color:black">is very </span><span style="color:#0070c0">close to the original signal waveform.</span></span> </span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.68pt; text-align:left"><span style="font-size:32.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0"><span style="font-size:12px"><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/Picture27.png" style="height:96px; width:373px" /></span></span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.68pt; text-align:left">&nbsp;</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify">&nbsp;</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n', '', '', 'IA 2'),
('18EC751', '', 'Module 3', 'CO  3', 'KL 4', 10, '<span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Analyse the working of Pulse Width Modulation (PWM) with block diagram. </span></span></p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 2886, '<span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Working of Pulse Width Modulation (PWM)&nbsp;</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Block diagram</span></span></p>\r\n', '<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">When the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">width of a relatively higher-frequency carrier signal </span><span style="color:black">comprising of </span><span style="color:#0070c0">discrete pulses </span><span style="color:black">is </span><span style="color:#0070c0">varied in accordance with the amplitude</span><span style="color:black"> of the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">analog modulating signal</span><span style="color:black">, it is called </span><span style="color:#0070c0">pulse width modulation (PWM).</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">amplitude</span><span style="color:black"> of the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">pulse remains constant </span><span style="color:black">and </span><span style="color:#0070c0">does not carry any information.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0">PWM provides better noise immunity</span><span style="color:black"> and </span><span style="color:#0070c0">allows use of amplitude limiters.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">It is also known as </span><span style="color:#0070c0">pulse duration modulation (PDM).</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">PWM technique is illustrated in Fig.</span></span> </span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/Picture28.png" style="height:353px; width:492px" /></span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify">\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">In </span><span style="color:#0070c0">pulse width modulation</span><span style="color:black">, the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">information signal modulates the width </span><span style="color:black">of the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">pulse signal according to its instantaneous value</span><span style="color:black"> while </span><span style="color:#0070c0">keeping the amplitude and position of the pulse constant.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">larger the sample value</span><span style="color:black">, the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">wider the corresponding pulse and vice versa.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">PWM is a </span><span style="color:#0070c0">non-linear form of modulation </span><span style="color:black">as compared to </span><span style="color:#0070c0">PAM which is linear form of modulation.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">If the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">information signal is slowly varying</span><span style="color:black">, that is, </span><span style="color:#0070c0">sampled at a fast rate compared to the Nyquist rate,</span><span style="color:black"> and then the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">adjacent pulses have almost the same width.</span></span> </span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify">\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><strong>Advantage and Disadvantage of PWM </strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">PWM has certain distinct advantages such as</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.68pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">It is </span><span style="color:#0070c0">easier to detect</span><span style="color:black">.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.68pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">It has </span><span style="color:#0070c0">very good noise immunity</span><span style="color:black">.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.68pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">There is </span><span style="color:#0070c0">no need of synchronization</span><span style="color:black">.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">PWM has some disadvantages such as</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.68pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Its </span><span style="color:#0070c0">signal power varies </span><span style="color:black">due to </span><span style="color:#0070c0">variable pulse width.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.68pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">transmission bandwidth </span><span style="color:black">required for a </span><span style="color:#0070c0">PWM signal is larger than that of PAM signal</span><span style="color:black">.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.68pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Due to the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">randomness of the width</span><span style="color:black">, it is </span><span style="color:#0070c0">not suitable for time-division multiplexing.</span></span> </span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.68pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><strong>Generation of PWM Signals</strong></span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.68pt; text-align:justify">\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Figure depicts a </span><span style="color:#0070c0">simplified block diagram of PWM signal generation using a comparator</span><span style="color:black">.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">information signal </span><span style="color:black">is </span><span style="color:#0070c0">applied to the non-inverting (+) input terminal </span><span style="color:black">of the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">comparator</span></span> <span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0">device.</span></span> </span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">A </span><span style="color:#0070c0">sawtooth signal operating </span><span style="color:black">at the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">carrier frequency is applied to the inverting </span><span style="color:black">(&ndash;) </span><span style="color:#0070c0">input of the comparator.</span></span> </span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0"><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/Picture29.png" style="height:174px; width:398px" /></span></span></span></div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.68pt; text-align:justify">\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><strong>Demodulation of PWM Signals</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">principle of operation of demodulation of PPM </span><span style="color:black">signals can be </span><span style="color:#0070c0">simply descried by time-averaging </span><span style="color:black">of </span><span style="color:#0070c0">PWM signals</span><span style="color:black">, followed by an </span><span style="color:#0070c0">averaging low-pass filter</span><span style="color:black">.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">A </span><span style="color:#0070c0">ramp signal </span><span style="color:black">is started at the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">positive edge and stopped at the negative edge of PWM signal. </span><span style="color:black">This operation is called </span><span style="color:#0070c0">time-averaging of the incoming signal.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">resultant ramp signal </span><span style="color:black">will have </span><span style="color:#0070c0">different heights </span><span style="color:black">in </span><span style="color:#0070c0">each cycle depending on the corresponding pulse width of incoming PWM signal.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Thus, the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">output is directly proportional </span><span style="color:black">to the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">pulse width </span><span style="color:black">which in turn </span><span style="color:#0070c0">represents the amplitude of the information signal.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">output of low-pass filter </span><span style="color:black">will follow the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">envelope</span><span style="color:black"> which is basically approximate </span><span style="color:#0070c0">replica of the information signal.</span></span></span></div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n', '', '', 'IA 2');
INSERT INTO `question_master2` (`course_code`, `CID`, `mo`, `co`, `kl`, `marks`, `question`, `r1`, `remarks1`, `r2`, `remarks2`, `r3`, `remarks3`, `final`, `q_id`, `question_number`, `qno`, `key1`, `scheme`, `cat2`, `ete`, `IA`) VALUES
('18EC751', '', 'Module 3', 'CO  3', 'KL 2', 10, '<span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Explain the working of Pulse Position Modulation (PPM). </span></span></p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 2887, '<span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Working of Pulse Position Modulation (PPM)</span></span></p>\r\n', '<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">When the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">position of a relatively higher frequency carrier signal </span><span style="color:black">comprising of </span><span style="color:#0070c0">discrete pulses </span><span style="color:black">is </span><span style="color:#0070c0">varied in accordance with the amplitude of the analog modulating signal,</span><span style="color:black"> it is called </span><span style="color:#0070c0">Pulse Position Modulation (PPM).</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">In </span><span style="color:#0070c0">PPM</span><span style="color:black">, the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">position of the pulses </span><span style="color:black">which is </span><span style="color:#0070c0">changed with respect to position of reference pulse.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">amplitude and width </span><span style="color:black">of the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">pulses remains unchanged and does not carry any information.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0">PPM provides better noise immunity </span><span style="color:black">and </span><span style="color:#0070c0">allows use of amplitude limiters.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0">PPM technique is illustrated </span><span style="color:black">in Figure</span></span> </span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/Picture30.png" style="height:356px; width:504px" /></span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify">\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><strong>Advantage and Disadvantage of PPM </strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">PPM has certain distinct advantages such as</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.68pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">It is </span><span style="color:#0070c0">easier to detect</span><span style="color:black">.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.68pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">It has </span><span style="color:#0070c0">very good noise.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.68pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0">PPM signal power is constant</span><span style="color:black">.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">PPM has some disadvantages such as</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.68pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0">PPM signals do need synchronization.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.68pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">transmission bandwidth</span><span style="color:black"> required for a </span><span style="color:#0070c0">PPM signal is also quite large.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">randomness in position </span><span style="color:black">in </span><span style="color:#0070c0">PPM</span><span style="color:black"> do not make it suitable for </span><span style="color:#0070c0">time-division multiplexing</span><span style="color:black">.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><strong>Generation of PPM Signal</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">simplest method of generating PPM signal </span><span style="color:black">is from PWM signal.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">relationship between PPM and PWM</span><span style="color:black"> can be seen from the fact that while the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">position of the pulse varies in PPM</span><span style="color:black">, the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">location of the trailing edge of the pulse varies in PWM</span><span style="color:black">.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Figure depicts a </span><span style="color:#0070c0">simplified block diagram of PPM </span><span style="color:black">signal generation from </span><span style="color:#0070c0">PWM signal</span><span style="color:black">.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">PWM signal is applied to an inverter </span><span style="color:black">which </span><span style="color:#0070c0">reverses polarity of the input pulse signals.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">output of the inverter </span><span style="color:black">is then </span><span style="color:#0070c0">applied to a differentiator.</span></span> </span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0"><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/Picture31.png" style="height:117px; width:573px" /></span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify">\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">When the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">PWM signal input</span><span style="color:black"> make </span><span style="color:#0070c0">transition from high to low, </span><span style="color:black">the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">output of differentiator </span><span style="color:black">consists of </span><span style="color:#0070c0">positive spikes.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">When the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">PWM signal input </span><span style="color:black">make </span><span style="color:#0070c0">transition from low to high, </span><span style="color:black">the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">output of differentiator consists of negative spikes.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">These </span><span style="color:#0070c0">spikes are fed </span><span style="color:black">to a </span><span style="color:#0070c0">positive edge triggered fixed-width pulse generator.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0">Pulses of fixed width </span><span style="color:black">are </span><span style="color:#0070c0">generated</span><span style="color:black"> when a </span><span style="color:#0070c0">positive spike appears at its input.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">occurrences of falling edges </span><span style="color:black">of </span><span style="color:#0070c0">PWM signal </span><span style="color:black">are </span><span style="color:#0070c0">proportional to amplitude </span><span style="color:black">of the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">original information signal.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Therefore, the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">delay in occurrence </span><span style="color:black">of these </span><span style="color:#0070c0">fixed width pulses are proportional to the amplitude of the input information signal at that instant.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">final output is PPM signal </span><span style="color:black">where </span><span style="color:#0070c0">positions of the pulses carry original information signal.</span></span> </span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify">\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:left"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><strong>Demodulation of PPM Signal</strong></span></span> </span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">A</span></span> <span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0">PPM demodulator circuit </span><span style="color:black">can be </span><span style="color:#0070c0">realized using transistor </span><span style="color:black">and </span><span style="color:#0070c0">RC combinations </span><span style="color:black">for </span><span style="color:#0070c0">ramp generation and filtering.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">As an </span><span style="color:#0070c0">alternate arrangement </span><span style="color:black">for </span><span style="color:#0070c0">PPM demodulator </span><span style="color:black">is to </span><span style="color:#0070c0">convert PPM signal to PWM signal</span><span style="color:black">, followed by use of </span><span style="color:#0070c0">PWM demodulator to recover the information signal.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">In </span><span style="color:#0070c0">PPM demodulator</span><span style="color:black">, the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">ramp signal starts at one positive edge of the pulse and stops at the positive edge </span><span style="color:black">of the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">next pulse.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Thus the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">gap between positive edges </span><span style="color:black">of </span><span style="color:#0070c0">two successive pulses received in PPM signal </span><span style="color:black">determines </span><span style="color:#0070c0">the height of the ramp signal generated.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">This, in turn, closely follows the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">amplitude of the information signal.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">This </span><span style="color:#0070c0">signal </span><span style="color:black">is then </span><span style="color:#0070c0">applied to a low-pass filter </span><span style="color:black">which </span><span style="color:#0070c0">filters out the envelope information as demodulated signal.</span></span></span></div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n', '', '', 'IA 2'),
('18EC32', '', 'Module 3', 'CO  3', 'KL 3', 10, '<span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif">Calculate the mesh currents using Mesh Current Analysis.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/q20.jpg" style="height:213px; width:300px" /></span></span></p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 2888, '<span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif">Step-1: 2 Marks</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:36.0pt; margin-right:0cm"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif">Step-2: 2 Marks</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:36.0pt; margin-right:0cm"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif">Step-3: 2 Marks</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:36.0pt; margin-right:0cm"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif">Step-4: 2 Marks</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:36.0pt; margin-right:0cm"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif">Step-5: 2 Marks</span></span></p>\r\n', '<img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/q20-s.jpg" style="height:218px; width:500px" /></p>\r\n', '', '', 'IA 2'),
('18EC751', '', 'Module 3', 'CO  3', 'KL 4', 10, '<span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Analyse the working of Pulse-Code Modulation (PCM). </span></span></p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 2889, '<span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Working of Pulse-Code Modulation (PCM)</span></span></p>\r\n', '<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0">Pulse-Code Modulation (PCM) </span><span style="color:black">is a type of </span><span style="color:#0070c0">signal-encoding technique</span><span style="color:black"> in which the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">analog information signal is sampled </span><span style="color:black">and the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">amplitude of each sample </span><span style="color:black">is </span><span style="color:#0070c0">approximated to the nearest one </span><span style="color:black">of a </span><span style="color:#0070c0">finite set of discrete levels,</span><span style="color:black"> so that </span><span style="color:#0070c0">both amplitude and time </span><span style="color:black">are </span><span style="color:#0070c0">represented in discrete form</span><span style="color:black">.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">With PCM, the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">continuously-varying analog signals </span><span style="color:black">are </span><span style="color:#0070c0">converted into pulses of fixed amplitude and fixed duration.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">PCM is a </span><span style="color:#0070c0">binary system </span><span style="color:black">where a </span><span style="color:#0070c0">pulse or no pulse within a prescribed time slot </span><span style="color:black">represents either a </span><span style="color:#0070c0">logic 1 or logic 0 condition.</span></span> </span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify">\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><strong>PCM System Block Diagram</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">operation of PCM system </span><span style="color:black">is briefly described below.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">band-pass filter (BPF) limits </span><span style="color:black">the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">frequency </span><span style="color:black">of the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">input analog information signal </span><span style="color:black">to standard </span><span style="color:#0070c0">voice-band frequency range </span><span style="color:black">of 300 Hz &ndash; 3000 Hz.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">sample-and-hold circuit periodically samples the analog input signal</span><span style="color:black"> and </span><span style="color:#0070c0">converts these samples to a multi-level PAM signal.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">analog-to-digital (A/D) converter converts </span><span style="color:black">the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">PAM samples to parallel PCM codes.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0">PCM codes are converted </span><span style="color:black">to </span><span style="color:#0070c0">serial binary data </span><span style="color:black">in the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">parallel-to-serial converter </span><span style="color:black">and then </span><span style="color:#0070c0">presented to the transmission line as serial digital pulses.</span></span> </span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0"><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/Picture32.png" style="height:434px; width:492px" /></span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify">\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">An </span><span style="color:#0070c0">analog signal </span><span style="color:black">is </span><span style="color:#0070c0">converted to a pulse code modulation signal</span><span style="color:black"> through three essential </span><span style="color:#0070c0">processes-sampling, quantization and encoding.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">transmission line repeaters </span><span style="color:black">are placed at prescribed distances to </span><span style="color:#0070c0">regenerate the digital pulses </span><span style="color:black">and </span><span style="color:#0070c0">enable to remove interference, if any, due to channel noise.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">In the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">PCM receiver</span><span style="color:black">, the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">serial-to-parallel converter converts serial pulses </span><span style="color:black">received from the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">transmission line to parallel PCM codes.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">digital-to-analog (D/A) converter generates sequence of quantized multi-level sampled pulses</span><span style="color:black">, resulting in </span><span style="color:#0070c0">reconstituted PAM signal</span><span style="color:black">.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">hold circuit </span><span style="color:black">is basically a </span><span style="color:#0070c0">low-pass filter (LPF) </span><span style="color:black">to </span><span style="color:#0070c0">reject any frequency component </span><span style="color:black">lying </span><span style="color:#0070c0">outside its baseband.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">It </span><span style="color:#0070c0">converts the recovered PAM </span><span style="color:black">signal back to its </span><span style="color:#0070c0">original analog form.</span></span></span></div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n', '', '', 'IA 2'),
('18EC751', '', 'Module 3', 'CO  3', 'KL 3', 10, '<span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Illustrate the Quantization of signals and discuss the classification of Quantization process. </span></span></p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 2890, '<span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Quantization of signals&nbsp;</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">classification of Quantization process</span></span></p>\r\n', '<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">conversion of an analog sample of the information signal into discrete form </span><span style="color:black">is known as </span><span style="color:#0070c0">quantization</span><span style="color:black">. Thus, an </span><span style="color:#0070c0">infinite number of possible levels </span><span style="color:black">are </span><span style="color:#0070c0">converted to a finite number of conditions.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><strong>Process&nbsp; of quantization</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">peak-to-peak range </span><span style="color:black">of the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">input sample values </span><span style="color:black">is </span><span style="color:#0070c0">subdivided</span><span style="color:black"> into a </span><span style="color:#0070c0">finite set of decision levels </span><span style="color:black">or </span><span style="color:#0070c0">decision thresholds.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">output </span><span style="color:black">is assigned a </span><span style="color:#0070c0">discrete value selected </span><span style="color:black">from a </span><span style="color:#0070c0">finite set of representation levels.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">A </span><span style="color:#0070c0">quantizer</span></span> <span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">is </span><span style="color:#0070c0">memory less </span><span style="color:black">in the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">sense that the quantizer output </span><span style="color:black">is determined only by the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">value </span><span style="color:black">of a </span><span style="color:#0070c0">corresponding input sample only.</span></span> </span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify">\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><strong>Definitions</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0"><strong>Quantization Interval: </strong></span><span style="color:black">Quantization interval is defined as the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">difference in magnitude levels between adjacent steps.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0"><strong>Quantum Overload Distortion: </strong></span><span style="color:black">Quantum overload distortion occurs when the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">magnitude of the sample exceeds the highest quantization interval.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0"><strong>Resolution: </strong></span><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">resolution</span><span style="color:black"> is defined as the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">voltage level of the minimum step-size, which is equal to the voltage of the least significant bit of PCM code.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">It is also the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">minimum voltage </span><span style="color:black">(other than 0 V) that can be </span><span style="color:#0070c0">decoded by digital-to-analog converter </span><span style="color:black">in the PCM receiver.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><strong>Implications of quantization</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The process of </span><span style="color:#0070c0">quantization</span><span style="color:black"> involves </span><span style="color:#0070c0">rounding off sample values </span><span style="color:black">of an </span><span style="color:#0070c0">analog signal </span><span style="color:black">to the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">nearest permissible level of the quantizer.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">As a result, the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">quantization error is produced.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0">Quantization error</span><span style="color:black"> is defined as the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">difference between rounding off sampling values of an analog signal to the nearest permissible level </span><span style="color:black">of the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">quantizer during the process of quantization.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">quantization error is directly proportional </span><span style="color:black">to the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">difference between consecutive quantization levels.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">quantization error is inversely proportional </span><span style="color:black">to the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">number of levels for amplitude range.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><strong>Classification of Quantization Process</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Depending upon the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">process of quantization </span><span style="color:black">to </span><span style="color:#0070c0">distribute quantization levels </span><span style="color:black">to be </span><span style="color:#0070c0">uniformly spaced or not, the quantization </span><span style="color:black">can be </span><span style="color:#0070c0">categorized </span><span style="color:black">as</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div class="O1" style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.81in; margin-top:6.24pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0">Uniform quantization</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div class="O1" style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.81in; margin-top:6.24pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0">Non-uniform quantization</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div class="O1" style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.81in; margin-top:6.24pt; text-align:justify">\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><strong>Uniform Quantizer</strong></span></span> </span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">A </span><span style="color:#0070c0">uniform quantizer is a quantizer</span></span> <span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">in which the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">quantization levels (step size) are uniformly spaced </span><span style="color:black">over the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">complete input range.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">It has </span><span style="color:#0070c0">linear characteristics.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">maximum quantization error </span><span style="color:black">remains same over the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">complete input range.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">signal-to-noise ratio does not remain same </span><span style="color:black">over the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">complete input range.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><strong>Non-uniform&nbsp; Quantizer</strong></span></span> </span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">A </span><span style="color:#0070c0">non-uniform Quantizer</span></span> <span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">is a </span><span style="color:#0070c0">quantizer in which the quantization levels</span><span style="color:black"> (step-size) </span><span style="color:#0070c0">vary according to the instantaneous value of the input signal level.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">It has </span><span style="color:#0070c0">nonlinear characteristics.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">step size varies </span><span style="color:black">according to the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">signal level </span><span style="color:black">to maintain </span><span style="color:#0070c0">the signal-to-noise ratio adequately high.</span></span></span></div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n', '', '', 'IA 2'),
('18EC751', '', 'Module 3', 'CO  3', 'KL 2', 10, '<span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">An analog information signal at the input to a &mu;-law compressor (m = 255) is positive, with its voltage level one-half the maximum value. What proportion of the maximum output voltage level would be produced at the output of compressor? </span></span></p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 2891, '<span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Proportion of the maximum output voltage level produced at the output of compressor</span></span></p>\r\n', '<p><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/Capture10.PNG" style="height:313px; width:915px" /></p>\r\n', '', '', 'IA 2'),
('18EC751', '', 'Module 3', 'CO  4', 'KL 2', 10, '<span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Explain the step-by-step procedure for &mu;-law and A-law standard companding processes for 256 quantization levels. </span></span></p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 2892, '<span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Step-by-step procedure for &mu;-law and A-law standard companding processes for 256 quantization levels</span></span></p>\r\n', '<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Create the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">logarithmic curves </span><span style="color:black">for the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">input signal </span><span style="color:black">during the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">compression part of companding &mu;-law and <em>A</em>-law</span><span style="color:black">.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0">Calculate the linear approximation </span><span style="color:black">of the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">logarithmic curve</span><span style="color:black">. &mu;-law and <em>A</em>-law calculate the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">linear approximation differently</span><span style="color:black">.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Since given number of </span><span style="color:#0070c0">quantization levels is 256</span><span style="color:black">, divide the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">curve into 8 positive and 8 negative segments, with 16 quantization intervals per segment.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Because of </span><span style="color:#0070c0">logarithmic increase</span><span style="color:black">, each </span><span style="color:#0070c0">successive segment </span><span style="color:black">is </span><span style="color:#0070c0">twice the length of the previous segment</span><span style="color:black">. &mu;-law and <em>A</em>-law have </span><span style="color:#0070c0">different segment lengths because of different calculations of linear approximations.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Use </span><span style="color:#0070c0">8 bit code words </span><span style="color:black">for each </span><span style="color:#0070c0">quantization interval</span><span style="color:black">, thereby resulting into </span><span style="color:#0070c0">256 code words</span><span style="color:black">.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div class="O1" style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.81in; margin-top:4.8pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">first bit of each code word represents the polarity </span><span style="color:black">of quantization interval.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div class="O1" style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.81in; margin-top:4.8pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">next three bits represent the segment number</span><span style="color:black">.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div class="O1" style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.81in; margin-top:4.8pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Last </span><span style="color:#0070c0">four bits indicate the quantization interval </span><span style="color:black">within the segment.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.28pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">bit rate </span><span style="color:black">can be </span><span style="color:#0070c0">calculated by multiplying the sampling rate </span><span style="color:black">(twice the input frequency) by the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">size of the codeword</span><span style="color:black">. For example, </span><span style="color:#0070c0">8 bit code words</span><span style="color:black"> allow for a </span><span style="color:#0070c0">bit rate of 64 kbps </span><span style="color:black">corresponding to </span><span style="color:#0070c0">4 kHz signal.</span></span></span></div>\r\n', '', '', 'IA 2');
INSERT INTO `question_master2` (`course_code`, `CID`, `mo`, `co`, `kl`, `marks`, `question`, `r1`, `remarks1`, `r2`, `remarks2`, `r3`, `remarks3`, `final`, `q_id`, `question_number`, `qno`, `key1`, `scheme`, `cat2`, `ete`, `IA`) VALUES
('18EC751', '', 'Module 4', 'CO  4', 'KL 3', 10, '<span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Classify the various types of digital Modulation. </span></span></p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 2893, '<span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Various types of digital Modulation</span></span></p>\r\n', '<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><strong>Digital modulation </strong>involves the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">process of amplitude, frequency, or phase of an analog carrier signal </span><span style="color:black">as a function of </span><span style="color:#0070c0">two or more than two finite, discrete states</span><span style="color:black">.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><strong>Binary Modulation </strong>is the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">process of varying amplitude, frequency, or phase of an analog carrier signal </span><span style="color:black">as a function of </span><span style="color:#0070c0">two finite, discrete states </span><span style="color:black">(0 and 1).</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><strong>Digital Modulation Types</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Let the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">information signal </span><span style="color:black">be a </span><span style="color:#0070c0">digital data sequence </span><span style="color:black">consisting of 1s and 0s.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Let the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">time-varying carrier signal </span><span style="color:black">be a </span><span style="color:#0070c0">high-frequency analog sinusoidal signal </span><span style="color:black">of the form:</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:center"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">vc(t) = Vc sin(2&pi;</span></span> <span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">fct + &theta;)</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">where </span><span style="color:#0070c0">Vc is the maximum amplitude </span><span style="color:black">(volts), </span><span style="color:#0070c0">fc is the carrier signal frequency </span><span style="color:black">(Hz), and </span><span style="color:#0070c0">&theta; is phase shift </span><span style="color:black">(radians) of the carrier signal.</span></span> </span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.0pt; text-align:justify">\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">There may be various possibilities for the process of modulation such as</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.4pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">If the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">amplitude (Vc) of the carrier signal </span><span style="color:black">is varied in proportion to the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">digital information signal</span><span style="color:black">, a </span><span style="color:#0070c0">digitally modulated signal known as <strong>amplitude shift keying (ASK) </strong></span><span style="color:black">is produced. </span><span style="color:#0070c0">One binary digit </span><span style="color:black">(0 or 1) is represented by the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">presence of a carrier signal</span><span style="color:black">; the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">other binary digit </span><span style="color:black">(1 or 0) is </span><span style="color:#0070c0">represented by the absence of a carrier signal</span><span style="color:black">. The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">frequency of the carrier signal remains unchanged</span><span style="color:black">.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.4pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">If the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">frequency (fc) of the carrier signal </span><span style="color:black">is </span><span style="color:#0070c0">varied in proportion </span><span style="color:black">to the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">digital information signal</span><span style="color:black">, a digitally modulated signal known as </span><span style="color:#0070c0"><strong>frequency shift keying (FSK) </strong></span><span style="color:black">is produced. </span><span style="color:#0070c0">Two binary digits </span><span style="color:black">(0 and 1) are represented by </span><span style="color:#0070c0">two different frequencies </span><span style="color:black">around the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">carrier signal frequency</span><span style="color:black">. The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">amplitude of the carrier signal remains unchanged</span><span style="color:black">.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.4pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">If the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">phase-angle (&theta;) of the carrier signal </span><span style="color:black">is varied in proportion to the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">digital information signal</span><span style="color:black">, a digitally modulated signal known as </span><span style="color:#0070c0"><strong>phase shift keying (PSK)</strong></span><span style="color:black"> is produced.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.4pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">If both the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">amplitude and phase-angle </span><span style="color:black">of the carrier signal are varied in proportion to the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">digital information signal</span><span style="color:black">, a digitally modulated signal known as </span><span style="color:#0070c0"><strong>Quadrature Amplitude Modulation (QAM) </strong></span><span style="color:black">is produced.</span></span> </span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.4pt; text-align:justify">\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><strong>Design Features of Digital Modulation</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.68pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0">Maximum data rate</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.68pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0">Minimum transmitted power</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.68pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0">Maximum utilization of available channel bandwidth</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.68pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0">Minimum probability of symbol error</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.68pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0">Maximum resistance to interfering signals</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.68pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0">Minimum system complexity</span></span> </span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.68pt; text-align:justify">\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><strong>Bit rate and Baud Rate</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.68pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0"><strong>Bit rate </strong></span><span style="color:black">refers to the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">rate of change of a binary data</span><span style="color:black">. It is expressed in </span><span style="color:#0070c0">bits per second</span><span style="color:black">, or simply bps.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.68pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0"><strong>Baud rate</strong></span><span style="color:black"><strong>, </strong>or </span><span style="color:#0070c0">simply baud</span><span style="color:black">, refers to the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">rate of change of a signal element </span><span style="color:black">(a signaling element may represent several information bits) after the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">process of encoding and modulation.</span><span style="color:black"> It is expressed as symbols per second.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.68pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0">Baud rate is also known as transmission rate</span><span style="color:black">, </span><span style="color:#0070c0">modulation rate, or symbol rate</span></span> </span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.68pt; text-align:justify">\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><strong>Limiting factor of transmitting digital data over analog channel</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">digital encoded data </span><span style="color:black">is in the form of </span><span style="color:#0070c0">sequences of pulses</span><span style="color:black">.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">In the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">frequency domain</span><span style="color:black">, these pulses contain </span><span style="color:#0070c0">frequency range starting from 0 to infinity</span><span style="color:black">.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">These </span><span style="color:#0070c0">pulses can be transmitted </span><span style="color:black">without any </span><span style="color:#0070c0">distortion over a communication channel </span><span style="color:black">having an </span><span style="color:#0070c0">infinite bandwidth</span><span style="color:black">. </span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">All types of communication channels such as </span><span style="color:#0070c0">telephone lines, optical fiber, microwave, or satellite links, are band-limited, </span><span style="color:black">and represent bandpass channels.</span></span> </span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify">\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><strong>Transmission of digital data over bandpass channels</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:8.64pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">digital data </span><span style="color:black">has to be </span><span style="color:#0070c0">first converted into a suitable form </span><span style="color:black">which is </span><span style="color:#0070c0">compatible to band-limited communication channel</span><span style="color:black">.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:8.64pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">So it is required to </span><span style="color:#0070c0">modulate</span><span style="color:black"> the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">digital data on a sinusoidal carrier signal </span><span style="color:black">for transmission over a </span><span style="color:#0070c0">bandpass channel</span><span style="color:black">.</span></span></span></div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n', '', '', 'IA 2'),
('18EC751', '', 'Module 4', 'CO  4', 'KL 4', 10, '<span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Analyse the working of Amplitude shift keying (ASK) with block diagram. </span></span></p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 2894, '<span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Working of Amplitude shift keying (ASK)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Block diagram. </span></span></p>\r\n', '<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0">Amplitude shift keying (ASK) </span><span style="color:black">is a form of </span><span style="color:#0070c0">digital modulation technique </span><span style="color:black">in which the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">amplitude of the analog sinusoidal carrier signal is varied to represent the input digital data.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Both </span><span style="color:#0070c0">frequency and phase of the carrier signal remains constant</span><span style="color:black"> while its </span><span style="color:#0070c0">amplitude changes in accordance with the levels of digital data.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Mathematically, the ASK signal can be expressed as:</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/Picture33.png" style="height:88px; width:427px" /></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">where </span><span style="color:#0070c0">Vc is the maximum amplitude </span><span style="color:black">of analog carrier signal in volts, and </span><span style="color:#0070c0">fc is the carrier frequency </span><span style="color:black">in Hz.</span></span> </span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify">\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">modulated ASK signal </span><span style="color:black">is </span><span style="color:#0070c0">either the carrier signal </span><span style="color:black">(for binary 1) or </span><span style="color:#0070c0">no carrier signal </span><span style="color:black">(for binary 0).</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">That simply means that the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">carrier signal is either ON or OFF,</span><span style="color:black"> depending on whether the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">digital information data is either binary 1 or 0, respectively.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">This is the reason that sometimes </span><span style="color:#0070c0">amplitude-shift keying is also referred to as On-Off Keying (OOK).</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Figure shows the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">waveforms for input digital information data, sinusoidal carrier signal, and the output ASK signal waveform</span><span style="color:black">.</span></span> </span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/Picture34.png" style="height:379px; width:574px" /></span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify">\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The following </span><span style="color:#0070c0">observations can be made from ASK signal waveform</span><span style="color:black">:</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">For </span><span style="color:#0070c0">every change in the input binary data stream</span><span style="color:black">, either from </span><span style="color:#0070c0">logic 1 to logic 0 </span><span style="color:black">or vice-versa, there is </span><span style="color:#0070c0">corresponding one change in the ASK signal waveform.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">For the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">entire duration </span><span style="color:black">of the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">input binary data logic 1 (high), the output ASK signal is a constant amplitude</span><span style="color:black">, </span><span style="color:#0070c0">constant-frequency sinusoidal carrier signal.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">For the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">entire duration of the input binary data logic 0 (low), the output ASK signal is zero </span><span style="color:black">(no carrier signal).</span></span> </span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify">\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:left"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><strong>ASK Bandwidth and Power Spectral Density (PSD) waveform</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">bandwidth of ASK signal </span><span style="color:black">is dependent on the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">bit rate of input data</span><span style="color:black">.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">duration of a bit (Tb) is the reciprocal of the bit rate. </span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">That is, bit rate, fb = 1/ Tb</span></span> </span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">time of one signaling element </span><span style="color:black">(Ts) is the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">reciprocal of the baud</span><span style="color:black">.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">In case of </span><span style="color:#0070c0">binary data</span><span style="color:black">, the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">time of one bit </span><span style="color:black">(Tb) is </span><span style="color:#0070c0">equal to the time of one signaling element </span><span style="color:black">(Ts).</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Therefore, the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">rate of change of the ASK signal </span><span style="color:black">(expressed in baud) is the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">same as the rate of change of the binary input data </span><span style="color:black">(expressed in bps).</span></span> </span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify">\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><strong>ASK Modulator</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0">ASK signal </span><span style="color:black">may be simply generated by applying the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">input binary data sequence and the sinusoidal carrier signal </span><span style="color:black">to the two inputs of a </span><span style="color:#0070c0">balance modulator</span><span style="color:black">.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Figure shows a </span><span style="color:#0070c0">simplified functional block diagram </span><span style="color:black">of ASK modulator.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The digital signal from a </span><span style="color:#0070c0">digital source </span><span style="color:black">is a </span><span style="color:#0070c0">unipolar NRZ </span><span style="color:black">signal which acts as the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">modulating signal </span><span style="color:black">input to the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">balance modulator</span><span style="color:black">.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The output of </span><span style="color:#0070c0">balance modulator </span><span style="color:black">is the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">product</span><span style="color:black"> of the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">NRZ signal and the sinusoidal carrier signal</span><span style="color:black">, that is</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:center"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">vASK (t) = vb(t) &times; vc(t)</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">where </span><span style="color:#0070c0">vb(t) = is the binary data input signal </span><span style="color:black">(1 or 0), and vc(t) = Vc</span></span> <span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">cos (2&pi;</span></span> <span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">fct) is the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">sinusoidal carrier signal</span><span style="color:black">.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The </span><span style="color:#0070c0">output</span><span style="color:black"> is passed through a </span><span style="color:#0070c0">bandpass filter </span><span style="color:black">in order to contain the </span><span style="color:#0070c0">frequency spectrum of the ASK signal</span><span style="color:black">.</span></span> </span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/Picture35.png" style="height:189px; width:642px" /></span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.48pt; text-align:justify">\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><strong>Coherent ASK Demodulator</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:#0070c0">Coherent ASK demodulator </span><span style="color:black">comprises of a </span><span style="color:#0070c0">balance modulator</span><span style="color:black">, followed by an </span><span style="color:#0070c0">integrator</span><span style="color:black"> and a </span><span style="color:#0070c0">decision making device</span><span style="color:black">.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Figure shows a </span><span style="color:#0070c0">simplified functional block diagram of coherent ASK demodulator</span><span style="color:black">.</span></span> </span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:30.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black"><span style="font-size:12px"><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/Picture36.png" style="height:250px; width:659px" /></span></span></span></span></div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n', '', '', 'IA 2'),
('18EC751', '', 'Module 4', 'CO  4', 'KL 2', 10, '<span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Explain the working of Frequency shift keying (FSK). </span></span></p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 2895, '<span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Working of Frequency shift keying (FSK)</span></span></p>\r\n', '<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Frequency shift keying (FSK) is a form of digital modulation technique in which the frequency of the analog sinusoidal carrier signal is varied to represent the input digital data. It has constant peak amplitude and phase.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Both amplitude and phase of the carrier signal remains constant while its frequency changes in accordance with the levels of digital data.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Mathematically, Binary FSK (BFSK) signal can be expressed as:</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/Picture37.png" style="height:83px; width:376px" /></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">where Vc is the maximum amplitude of analog carrier signal in volts, and f1 and f2 are typically offset frequencies from the carrier frequency fc by equal but opposite values.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Figure shows the time-domain waveforms for input digital data, sinusoidal carrier signal, and the output BFSK signal waveform.</span></span> </span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/Picture38.png" style="height:398px; width:582px" /></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:justify">\r\n<p style="margin-left:.38in; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The following observations can be made.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.68pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">When the input binary data changes from a binary logic 1 to logic 0 and vice versa, the BFSK output signal frequency shifts from f1 to f2 and vice versa (f1 &gt; f2).</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.68pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">The time duration of one bit (Tb) is the same as the symbol time duration (Ts) of the BFSK signal output.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.68pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Wingdings">&Oslash;</span><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;"><span style="color:black">Thus, the bit rate (fb) equals the baud rate.</span></span></span></div>\r\n</div>\r\n', '', '', 'IA 2'),
