('18EC72', '', 'Module 3', 'CO  3', 'KL 2', 10, '<span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,&quot;sans-serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">With a neat circuit diagram and waveform explain Domino gates.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 3009, 'Circuit diagram of Domino gates.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Explaination</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Waveform</p>\r\n', '<img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/b1.PNG" style="height:533px; width:413px" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/b2.PNG" style="height:235px; width:314px" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The monotonicity problem can be solved by placing a static CMOS inverter between dynamic gates, as shown in Figure 9.28(a). This converts the monotonically falling output into a monotonically rising signal suitable for the next gate, as shown in Figure 9.28(b).</p>\r\n', '', '', 'IA 2'),
