('18EC741', '', 'Module 2', 'CO  2', 'KL 1', 10, '<ol>\r\n	<li style="text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Calibri,&quot;sans-serif&quot;"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Define an IP Addressing. Briefly explain the following different classifications of IP addressing in the IOT.&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 2M + 8M</span></span></span>\r\n	<ol style="list-style-type:lower-alpha">\r\n		<li style="text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Calibri,&quot;sans-serif&quot;"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Static IP Address</span></span></span></li>\r\n		<li style="text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Calibri,&quot;sans-serif&quot;"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Dynamic IP Address</span></span></span></li>\r\n		<li style="text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Calibri,&quot;sans-serif&quot;"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">DNS</span></span></span></li>\r\n		<li style="text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">DHCP</span></span></li>\r\n	</ol>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 3091, 'Definition of IP Addressing&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;2M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Explanation of each classifications 2Mx4 = 8M</p>\r\n', '<span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif">IP version 4 address consists of 32 bits. However, it can be considered as four decimal numbers separated by dots.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0cm; margin-right:0cm; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif">For example: 198.136.56.2 for 32bits- 11000110 100010000011100000000010. Each decimal number is a value of an octet = 8 bits. IP address can be between 0.0.0.0 to 255.255.255.255; total there are 32 bit address.&nbsp;Three separate fields with a decimal number each for each set of 8 bits are easier to use.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0cm; margin-right:0cm; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><strong>Static IP Address:</strong>&nbsp;A static IP address is the one assigned by the internet service provider. The service provides may provide an individual just one address. When a company has a number of hosts, a service provider may provide a class C network address consisting of a group of 254 = 28- 2 IP address. The following example gives the classification A, B, C and D and how the allocations of static addresses are made to a group of hosts.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0cm; margin-right:0cm; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><strong>Dynamic IP Address:</strong>&nbsp;Once a device connects to the Internet, it needs to be allotted an individual IP address. When the device connects to a router, the router and device use the DHCP(Dynamic Host Control Protocol) which assigns an IP address at an instance to the device. This address is called dynamic IP address. When a device disconnects or switches off or the router boots again, then the dynamic IP address is lost and a new allocation takes place when the device reconnects.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0cm; margin-right:0cm; text-align:justify"><br />\r\n<span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><strong>DNS:</strong>&nbsp;Consider an IP address, 198.136.56.2 (11000110 10001000 00111000 00000010). It is difficult to remember or use. The domain name for the address is rajkamal.org. Access to web server hosted at the domain is made using the website name, http://www.rajkamal.org/. Access to mail-server hosted at the domain is made using the mail server name, http://mail.rajkamal.org/. Another example of domain name is mheducation.com/.<br />\r\n.com, .org, .in and .us are called Top Level Domain (TLD). A TLD can further be subdivided as .co.in or .gov.in or .gov.uk.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0cm; margin-right:0cm; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif">A registrar provides domain names at a certain cost per year. The DNS server at the Registrar has a control panel (cPanel) and can be configured using cPanel. Domain Names System(DNS) is an application which provides an IP address for a corresponding service from the named domain service.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><strong>DHCP</strong><br />\r\nWhen a sensor, actuator or IoT device or node needs to connect to the Internet, a server called DHCP server provides a dynamic IP address, subnet mask and ARP and RARP caches. The server (subnet) has its own IP address to provide connectivity to the Internet.<br />\r\nDynamic Host configuration Protocol(DHCP) is a protocol to dynamically provide new IP addresses and set subnet masks for the connected node so that it can use the subnet server and subnet router at the communication framework.</span></span></p>\r\n', '', '', 'IA 2'),
('18EC741', '', 'Module 2', 'CO  2', 'KL 1', 10, '<span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif">Define IPv6 Address and explain IPv6 addressing format. Distinguish between three different classes of Ipv6 addressing&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 2M+2M+6M</span></span></p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 3092, 'IPv6 definition&nbsp; 2M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>IPv6 Address format with suitable example&nbsp; &nbsp;2M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Three classes of IPv6 2Mx3 = 6M</p>\r\n', '<span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="font-size:12px">IPv6 Classifications</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0cm; margin-right:0cm; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="color:black">IPv6 addresses are classified into three classes. Each class differs in primary addressing and routing methods. An interface may be at a distinct node. </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0cm; margin-right:0cm; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="color:black">Unicast address is for a single network interface. 48 bit or more in unicast specify routing prefix. 16 bit or less specify a subnet id. 64 bit are interface identifiers. </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0cm; margin-right:0cm; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="color:black">Anycast address means address of a group of nodes or interfaces. A packet sent to an anycast address is delivered to just one of the member interfaces. One may be the nearest host. Nearest is measured according to the routing protocols definition of distance. </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0cm; margin-right:0cm; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="font-size:12px">Multicast address means an address used by multiple hosts, which acquires the multicast address destination by participating in the multicast distribution protocol among network routers. A packet with multicast address delivers to all interfaces that have joined the corresponding multicast group.</span></span></p>\r\n', '', '', 'IA 2'),
('18EC741', '', 'Module 2', 'CO  2', 'KL 1', 10, '<span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,&quot;sans-serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Define HTTP. List and briefly explain the important features of HTTP&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2M + 8M</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 3093, 'HTTP definition with port numbers&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 2M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Features of HTTP&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;8M</p>\r\n', '<span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif">HTTP Definition with the Port Number 80&nbsp; - 2M</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0cm; margin-right:0cm; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif">The important features of HTTP are:&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;8M</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="color:black">HTTP is the standard protocol for requesting a URL defined web-page resource, and for sending response to the web server. An HTTP client requests an HTTP server on the Internet and the server responds by sending a response. The response may be with or without applying a process.</span></span></span></li>\r\n	<li><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="color:black">HTTP is a stateless protocol.</span></span></span></li>\r\n	<li><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="color:black">HTTP is a file transfer-like protocol. We use it more efficiently than the FTP because in FTP, we have to give a certain command. </span></span></span></li>\r\n	<li><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="color:black">The HTTP protocol is very light and thus it works fast</span></span></span></li>\r\n	<li><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="color:black">HTTP based on Object Oriented Programming System (OOPS). </span></span></span></li>\r\n	<li><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="color:black">Eight HTTP specific specified methods and extension methods included : Namely 1. GET. 2. POST. 3. HEAD.</span>4. CONNECT. 5. PUT. 6. DELETE. 7. TRACE. 8. OPTIONS.</span></span></li>\r\n	<li><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="color:black">A provision of user authentication exits besides the basic authentication.</span></span></span></li>\r\n	<li><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="color:black">prevents the transmission of username and password </span></span></span></li>\r\n	<li><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="color:black">Byte range specification helps an HTTP server to send large response in parts.</span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', '', '', 'IA 2'),
('18EC741', '', 'Module 2', 'CO  2', 'KL 3', 10, '<span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="font-size:12px">Define UDP. List out the features of UDP.&nbsp; With neat block diagram explain the UDP header fields with data stack.&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 2M + 4M + 4M</span></span></p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 3094, 'UDP Definition 2M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>UDP Features 4M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>UDP header diagram and explanation 4M</p>\r\n', '<span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="color:black">UDP Universal Datagram Protocol, is a protocol for constrained environment and ROLL environment.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0cm; margin-right:0cm"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="color:black">Header fields are 2 words (1 word = 32 bits) and optionally of 4 words</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0cm; margin-right:0cm"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="color:black">Features:</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="color:black">UDP header has 2 words</span></span></span></li>\r\n	<li><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="color:black">Data stack to network has max m words where m &lt;= (2<sup>14 </sup>- 2). </span></span></span></li>\r\n	<li><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="color:black">Upper 16 bits are for source port number and </span></span></span></li>\r\n	<li><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="color:black">Lower 16 bits are for destination port number. </span></span></span></li>\r\n	<li><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="color:black">Header second word upper 16 bits are length </span></span></span></li>\r\n	<li><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="color:black">Lower 16 bits are checksum</span></span></span></li>\r\n	<li><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="color:black">Half-duplex un-acknowledged data flow from transport layer at one end to transport layer of another end</span></span></span></li>\r\n	<li><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="color:black">May or may not reach destination</span></span></span></li>\r\n	<li><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="color:black">Connectionless</span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/UDP%20header%281%29.jpg" style="float:left; height:342px; width:330px" /></p>\r\n', '', '', 'IA 2'),
('18EC741', '', 'Module 2', 'CO  2', 'KL 3', 10, '<span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="font-size:12px">With neat block diagram explain the cloud computing paradigm for Data collection, storage and computing</span></span></p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 3095, 'Block Diagram&nbsp; &nbsp; 5M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Explanation Data Collection, Storage and Cloud Infrastucture 5M</p>\r\n', '<img alt="" src="/svce/ece/qps/ckeditor/kcfinder/upload/images/Data%20Collections.jpg" style="float:left; height:285px; width:289px" />&nbsp;Explnation of IoT/M2M local device network wityh all its devices, Dedicated Data Store, Internet Firewall, Database Firewall , Data Centre, Server, IoT database&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '', '', 'IA 2'),
('18EC741', '', 'Module 2', 'CO  2', 'KL 3', 10, '<span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="font-size:12px">a) List out Cloud computing features and advantages&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 05M</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="font-size:12px">b) What are the concerns in usage of cloud computing&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 05M</span></span></p>\r\n', 'N', 'Knowledge Level is Inappropriate', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 3096, 'Features&nbsp; &nbsp;5M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Conceremns&nbsp; 5M</p>\r\n', 'a) Essential features of cloud storage and computing are:<br />\r\ni) On demand self-service to users for the provision of storage, computing servers, software delivery and server time<br />\r\nii) Resource pooling in multi-tenant model<br />\r\niii) Broad network accessibility in virtualized environment to heterogeneous users, clients, systems and devices<br />\r\niv) Elasticity<br />\r\nv) Massive scale availability<br />\r\nvi) Scalability<br />\r\nvii) Maintainability<br />\r\nviii) Homogeneity<br />\r\nix) Virtualilsation<br />\r\nx) Interconnectivity platform with virtualized environment for enterprises and provisioning of in-between Service Level agreements(SLAs)<br />\r\nxi) Resilient computing<br />\r\nxii) Advanced security<br />\r\nxiii) Low cost</p>\r\n\r\n<p>b) Concerns in usage of cloud computing are:<br />\r\ni) Requirements of a constant high speed Internet connection<br />\r\nii) Limitations of the services available<br />\r\niii) Possible data loss<br />\r\niv) Non delivery as per defined SLA specified performance<br />\r\nv) Different APIs and protocols used at different clouds<br />\r\nvi) Security in multi-tenant environment needs high trust and low risks<br />\r\nvii) Loss of users control</p>\r\n', '', '', 'IA 2'),
('18EC741', '', 'Module 2', 'CO  2', 'KL 3', 10, 'a)&nbsp;<span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,&quot;sans-serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Briefly explain the four different types of cloud deployment models&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 04M</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0cm; margin-right:0cm; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,&quot;sans-serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">b) What are the Cloud computing service features offered by Nimbits PaaS.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 06M</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 3097, 'a) Cloud Deployment Models&nbsp; &nbsp; 4M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>b) Nimbits Cloud features&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 6M</p>\r\n', '<span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif">a)&nbsp;<span style="color:black">Following are the four cloud deployment models: </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0cm; margin-right:0cm"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="color:black">1. Public cloud: This model is provisioned by educational institutions, industries, government institutions or businesses or enterprises and is open for public use. </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0cm; margin-right:0cm"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="color:black">2. Private cloud: This model is expensive for use by institutions, industries, businesses or enterprises and is meant for private use in the organization by the employees and associated users only. </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0cm; margin-right:0cm"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="color:black">3. Community cloud: This model is exclusive for use by a community formed by institutions, industries, businesses or enterprises, and for use within the community organization, employees and associated users. The community specifies security and compliance considerations. </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif">4. Hybrid cloud: A set of two or more distinct clouds (public, private or community) with distinct data stores and applications that bind between them to deploy the proprietary or standard technology.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif">b)&nbsp;</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0cm; margin-right:0cm"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="color:black"><strong>b) Nimbits Cloud Computing Service / Features</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0cm; margin-right:0cm"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="color:black">i) Edge computing locally on embedded systems, built up of local applications. It runs the rules and pushes important data up to the cloud running when connected over Internet and an instance of Nimbits Serverr hosts at the device nodes which is then enabled. </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0cm; margin-right:0cm"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="color:black">ii) It supports multiple programming languages, including Arduino, new Arduino library, push functions from Arduino cloud, Javascript, HTML or the Nimbits.io Java library. </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0cm; margin-right:0cm"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="color:black">iii) Nimbits server functions as a backend platform. Nimbits data point can relay data between the software systems or hardware devices such as Arduino using the cloud as a backend. </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0cm; margin-right:0cm"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="color:black">iv) An open source java library called nimbits.io enables easy development of JAVA, web and Android solutions (Nimbits data, alerts, messages on mobile) </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0cm; margin-right:0cm"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="color:black">v) It provides a rule engine for connecting sensors, persons and software to the cloud and one another. Rules can be for calculations, statistics, email alerts, xmpp messages, push notifications and more. </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0cm; margin-right:0cm"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="color:black">vi) It provides a data logging service and access and stores the historical data points and data objects. </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0cm; margin-right:0cm"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="color:black">vii) Storage in any format that can be serialized into a string, such as JSON or XML. </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0cm; margin-right:0cm"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="color:black">viii) It filters the noise and important changes sent to another larger central instance. </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0cm; margin-right:0cm"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="color:black">ix) It processes a specific type of data and can store it. </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif">x) Time or geo stamping of the data. </span></span></p>\r\n', '', '', 'IA 2'),
('18EC741', '', 'Module 2', 'CO  2', 'KL 3', 10, '<span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="font-size:12px">With neat block diagram explain various IoT Cloud Computing services offered by Nimbits&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 10M</span></span></p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 3098, 'Block Diagram&nbsp;of Nimbits Cloud Computing Services&nbsp; &nbsp;4M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Explanation of Nimbits services&nbsp; &nbsp;6M</p>\r\n', '', '', '', 'IA 2'),
('18EC741', '', 'Module 2', 'CO  2', 'KL 4', 10, '<span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="font-size:12px">With neat block diagram explain various IoT Cloud Computing services offered by Nimbits&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 10M</span></span></p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 3099, 'Block Diagram 4M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Explanation of Nimbits Cloud services 5=6M</p>\r\n', 'Block Diagram of Nimbits Cloud Services&nbsp; &nbsp; 4M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Explnation of all the blocks and the various operations in Nimbits Services&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;6M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '', '', 'IA 2'),
('18EC741', '', 'Module 2', 'CO  3', 'KL 3', 10, '<span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">a) Define I2C protocol.&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 02M</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">b) With neat block diagram, explain I2C serial protocol and its operations in IoT applications&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 08M</span></span></p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 3100, 'Definition of I2C Series Protcol&nbsp; &nbsp; 2M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Block Diagram of I2C, Explanation of SDA, SCL, Master and Slave Nodes&nbsp; &nbsp; 8M</p>\r\n', 'Block Diagram of I2C&nbsp; &nbsp;2M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Using I2C Serial Protocol&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;8M<br />\r\nI2C protocol is communication protocol for a serial bus that communicates in synchronous mode. A device transfers data as a master or slave. Master means the device can address and communicate with a number of slaves. Master sends clock pulses to the slave devices for synchronization. Maximum connected devices can be up to 127.<br />\r\nAt one instance, one device functions as a master and another as slave, and functioning depends on the internal circuit for I2C functions at the device.<br />\r\nAssume that a sensor has built-in ADC as well as I2C interface and communicates the bytes over I2C SDA and SCL pins.</p>\r\n', '', '', 'IA 2'),
('18EC741', '', 'Module 3', 'CO  3', 'KL 1', 10, '<span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif">With suitable block diagram explain the five levels for software development for applications and services for IoT or M2M&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;10M</span></span></p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 3101, 'List of Five Levels&nbsp; &nbsp; 5M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Explnation of Five levels and software development process&nbsp; &nbsp;5M&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n', 'Figure:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif">The devices connect, network and communicate over the web. They use the communication gateway, SOAP, REST, RESTful HTTP and Websockets.<br />\r\nFigure shows five levels for software development for applications and services in the IoT or M2M. the software needs are for the devices, local network, gateway, cloud/web connectivity and web/cloud APIs.<br />\r\nSoftware such as Eclipse IoT enable the development of software for the first, second and third levels. The software enables the device gateways connectivity to the Internet and cloud server. Eclipse IoT enables open source implementations of IoT protocols. The implementable protocols include MQTT CoAP, OMA-DM and OMA LWm2M and Internet Connectivity protocols.</span></span></p>\r\n', '', '', 'IA 2'),
('18EC741', '', 'Module 3', 'CO  3', 'KL 4', 10, '<span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,&quot;sans-serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Illustrate the following methods of Reading the data from sensors and devices&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 10M</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0cm; margin-right:0cm; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,&quot;sans-serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">a. Using ADC Analog Input</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0cm; margin-right:0cm; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,&quot;sans-serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">b. Using the Libraries</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0cm; margin-right:0cm; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,&quot;sans-serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">c. Using the Timers</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0cm; margin-right:0cm; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,&quot;sans-serif&quot;"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">d. Using Software Serial Library</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 3102, 'Reading the data&nbsp; &nbsp;-&nbsp; 2M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Explnation of each models 2Mx4 = 8M</p>\r\n', '<span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif">Using ADC Analog input<br />\r\nAssume a temperature sensor is used for measuring between 0 degree and 100 degrees Celsius. A sensor sends analog output at an analog input of a 10 bit ADC. An ADC output converts to serial by a parallel input to serial-output(PISO) converter. The serial output connects to the serial SPI input pin at Arduino Uno board. An RH% sensor can also be used in a similar manner where measured value is in RH% in place of degree Celsius.<br />\r\nThe ADC output for a sensor at 100 degrees is decimal 1023 (=binary 1111111111) and decimal 0 (=0000000000) for 0 degree.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif">Using the Libraries<br />\r\nIOT &amp; WSN (18EC751)<br />\r\n11 | P a g e D e p t . o f E C E P r a k a s h a G<br />\r\nThe library functions can directly be used during coding.<br />\r\nUsing the Timers<br />\r\nTimer functions are required in a number of applications. A number of timer libraries are available. A set of timer functions library is available online. MsTimer stands for millisecond timers with two states. It holds a simple usage. It has two functions set ( ) and start ( ). First one sets the timer for interrupt after a preset interval and second one to start running the timer.<br />\r\nUsing Software Serial Library<br />\r\nA serial interface library has functions to read and write as per serial protocols. A protocol based communication first transmits the header bits. These may include the address of the device or registers ( control, data, status or other registers). The data bits transmit after header bits and control bits, if any. End-bits transmit in the end. Each serial protocol has specific ways of formatting and sequencing during communication.<br />\r\nUART protocol based communication uses two signals, denoted by Tx or TxD(for serial transmission of header, data and other bits) and Rx or RxD(for serial reception). Assume that baud rate is 2400. Then, 240 times a new set of 8-bits data transmits in one second. 10 bits transmit for each set for data, character, command or address. A byte represents a character in a string, a sensed data and command for receiving device or address of destined or receiving device.</span></span></p>\r\n', '', '', 'IA 2'),
('18EC741', '', 'Module 3', 'CO  3', 'KL 4', 10, '<span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="font-size:12px">With neat block diagram examine the applications of connected street lights using MQTT &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 10M</span></span></p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 3103, '', 'MQTT Diagram</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif">A communication mode is pub-sub mode. MQTT protocol provides for three objects: MQTT clients at the devices, MQTT Broker and MQTT clients at the application(s). Assume that a&nbsp;device, such as a streetlight deploys MQTT client for sending the sensed data and receives commands from the application end through a broker ( intermediate server). MQTT-client unlike HTTP, does not have to pull the messages(commands) which the device needs for its control. An MQTT broker pushes the messages to the client, provided a client has subscribed to those. A broker functions like a dashboard, where the messages first reach from the sources and from there the messages then dispatch to the subscribers(ones who makes a request for the messages being dispatched).<br />\r\nEach MQTT client may be required to use an always connected UDP(or TCP) connection with a broker. The MQTT broker uses buffers for all messages. This facilitates the dispatch when a client reconnects after an interruption. An interruption is always a possibility in ROLL environment.<br />\r\nConsider use of MQTT Pub/Sub protocol for the connectivity between devices and the application layers. Figure below shows the connected streetlights publishing the sensed data and subscribing for the control data and using MQTT clients during communication with the application layer. The figure shows that MQTT clients communicate through an MQTT broker with other clients at the devices or at the applications and central controller. The figure also shows sequence 1, 2, 3 and 4 for message exchanges.</span></span></p>\r\n', '', '', 'IA 2'),
('18EC741', '', 'Module 3', 'CO  3', 'KL 3', 10, '<span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="font-size:12px">With neat diagram illustrate the 5 layered architecture for connected sensors and actuators for Android phone using MQTT client through MQTT broker&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;10M</span></span></p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 3104, 'Block diagram with 5 layered architecture&nbsp; &nbsp;5M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Explanation of each layered operations&nbsp; &nbsp; 5M</p>\r\n', 'Block diagram with 5 layered architecture&nbsp; &nbsp;5M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Explanation of each layered operations&nbsp; &nbsp; 5M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Physical Data Link Layer, Adaptation Layer, Network and Transport Layer, Application Support Layer and Application Layer</p>\r\n', '', '', 'IA 2'),
('18EC741', '', 'Module 4', 'CO  4', 'KL 1', 10, '<span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="font-size:12px">Briefly explain the privacy and Vulnerabilities of IoT&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 5M + 5M</span></span></p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 3105, 'Privacy elements and features of an IoT&nbsp; &nbsp; 5M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Vulnerabilities in IoT&nbsp; &nbsp;5M</p>\r\n', '<span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="font-size:12px">Privacy<br />\r\nMessage privacy means that the message should not reach into the hands of the unrelated entities. When data or messages communicate from the things (device platforms), they are meant only for the applications or services and for targeted things only.<br />\r\nPrivacy means no interference or disturbance from other. Consider an example of messages from embedded devices in an automobile using the Internet to an automobile service centre. Messages reach only the centre and used only by the services of the centre.</span></span><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="font-size:12px">Vulnerabilities of IoT<br />\r\nVulnerability means weak without complete protection, weakness to defend oneself or can be easily influenced from surrounding unwanted things from itself.<br />\r\nIoT network can be vulnerable to eavesdropping. Eavesdropper creates security issues. An eavesdropper say E listens to the messages and commands in the network during communication and obtains confidential messages.<br />\r\nA server at E sends fake commands which a server S for the devices data assumes that are from the devices and applications. S issues responses for the device operations in response to requests from E.<br />\r\nE listens these responses. A fake device at E can be used to send the device data, such as sensor data, requests and commands from E for disrupting the control system. Use of secret key encryption can protect the messages to and from device, server, application or service.<br />\r\nThe key is a device software generated string which can be cracked by trying large number of combinations. Device unique ID and authentication issues exist.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '', '', 'IA 2'),
('18EC741', '', 'Module 3', 'CO  3', 'KL 1', 10, '<span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="font-size:12px">List out the top ten identified vulnerabilities in IoT applications/services&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 10M</span></span></p>\r\n', 'N', 'Knowledge Level is Inappropriate', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 3106, 'List of 10 Vulnerabilities&nbsp; &nbsp;1Mx10 = 10M</p>\r\n', 'top ten vulnerabilities in IoT applications/services as follows:<br />\r\ni) Insecure web interface.<br />\r\nii) Insufficient authentication or authorisation<br />\r\niii) Insecure network services.<br />\r\niv) Lack of transport encryption/integrity verification<br />\r\nv) Privacy concerns<br />\r\nvi) Insecure cloud interface<br />\r\nvii) Insecure mobile interface<br />\r\nviii) Insufficient security configurability<br />\r\nix) Insecure software or firmware<br />\r\nx) Poor physical security</p>\r\n', '', '', 'IA 2');
INSERT INTO `question_master2` (`course_code`, `CID`, `mo`, `co`, `kl`, `marks`, `question`, `r1`, `remarks1`, `r2`, `remarks2`, `r3`, `remarks3`, `final`, `q_id`, `question_number`, `qno`, `key1`, `scheme`, `cat2`, `ete`, `IA`) VALUES
('18EC741', '', 'Module 3', 'CO  3', 'KL 3', 10, '<span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="font-size:12px">With a figure illustrate the security function group components in functional view in IoT reference architecture</span></span></p>\r\n', 'N', 'Knowledge Level is Inappropriate', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 3107, 'List of Security Requirements&nbsp; &nbsp; 10M</p>\r\n', '<span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="font-size:12px">Security Requirements<br />\r\nIoT reference architecture is a set of three architectural views- functional, information and deployment and operational.<br />\r\nSecurity FG contains five sets of functions which are required for ensuring security and privacy. Large number of devices, applications and services communicate in IoT.<br />\r\nFive functional components of security are defined in IoT reference architecture. Following are five functional components:<br />\r\ni) Identity management(IdM)</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="font-size:12px">ii) Authentications<br />\r\niii) Authorisation<br />\r\niv) Key exchange and management<br />\r\nv) Trust and reputation</span></span></p>\r\n', '', '', 'IA 2'),
('18EC741', '', 'Module 3', 'CO  3', 'KL 4', 10, '<span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="font-size:12px">With neat layered attacker model diagram explain the possible attacks at each layer of the IoT&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 10M</span></span></p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 3108, 'Diagram&nbsp; &nbsp; 5M</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Explanation&nbsp; &nbsp; 5M</p>\r\n', 'Following are the suggested solutions for mitigating the attacks on the layer:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Layer 1 attacks solution:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Solution depends on the device used.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Eg: link level provisioning of security uses-BT LE link level AES-CCM- 128 authenticated encryption algorithm for confidentiality &amp; authentication, &amp; ZigBee at link-level security using AES-CCM-128.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Layer 2 attacks solution:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Programming the network switches to prevent internal node attacks during use of DHCP or spanning tree protocol(STP).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Additional controls may include ARP inspection, disabling unused ports &amp; enforcing effective security on VLANs to prevent VLAN hopping.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>VLAN refers to a group of end stations with a common set of requirements independent of a physical location.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>VLANs have the same attributes as a physical LAN but allow you to group end stations even if they are not located physically on the same LAN segment.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LW M2M OMA specification for device gateway to the internet has provisions for MAS for security, root kay data store, &amp; device &amp; data authentication.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Layer 3 attacker solutions:</strong><br />\r\nUse of temper resistant router, use of packet filtering &amp; controlling routing messages &amp; packets data between layer 3 &amp; 4 through a firewall reduces the risks.<br />\r\n<strong>Layer 4 attacker solution:</strong><br />\r\nPort scanning method is a solution which identifies the vulnerable port.<br />\r\nA solution is the opening of network port &amp; configuring effectively the firewall, &amp; locking down ports only to those required.<br />\r\nA solution is DTLs between layers 4&amp;5.<br />\r\nThe DTLs has provisions for three types of security services, viz., integrity, authentication &amp; confidentiality.<br />\r\nA solution is include SASL(Simple Authentication &amp; Security Layer)for security when the XMPP protocol.<br />\r\n<strong>Layer 5 &amp; 6 attacker solution:</strong><br />\r\nAbove layer 4, we are looking primarily at application level attacks which are results for poor coding practices.<br />\r\nAssume an attacker injects the SQL input to extract data from the database. When the application fails to validate the injection the query extracts the data.</p>\r\n', '', '', 'IA 2'),
