 style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif">&ndash;Type of service</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div class="O1" style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.81in; margin-top:6.24pt; text-align:left"><span style="color:null"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif">&ndash;Quality of Service </span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div class="O1" style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.81in; margin-top:6.24pt; text-align:left"><span style="color:null"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif">&ndash;Fault tolerance </span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div class="O1" style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.81in; margin-top:6.24pt; text-align:left"><span style="color:null"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif">&ndash;Lifetime</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div class="O1" style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.81in; margin-top:6.24pt; text-align:left"><span style="color:null"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif">&ndash;Scalability</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div class="O1" style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.81in; margin-top:6.24pt; text-align:left"><span style="color:null"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif">&ndash;Wide range of densities</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div class="O1" style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.81in; margin-top:6.24pt; text-align:left"><span style="color:null"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif">&ndash;Programmability</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div class="O1" style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.81in; margin-top:6.24pt; text-align:left"><span style="color:null"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif">&ndash;Maintainability</span></span></span></div>\r\n', '', '', 'IA 2'),
('18EC741', '', 'Module 4', 'CO  4', 'KL 3', 10, '<span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="font-size:12px">Distinguish various required mechanisms used for efficient wireless sensor networks&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 8M</span></span></p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 3110, '<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.68pt; text-align:left"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="font-size:12px">&bull;<span style="color:black">Multihop wireless communication</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.68pt; text-align:left"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="font-size:12px">&bull;<span style="color:black">Energy-efficient operation</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.68pt; text-align:left"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="font-size:12px">&bull;<span style="color:black">Auto-configuration</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.68pt; text-align:left"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="font-size:12px">&bull;<span style="color:black">Collaboration and in-network processing</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.68pt; text-align:left"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="font-size:12px">&bull;<span style="color:black">Data centric</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.68pt; text-align:left"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="font-size:12px">&bull;<span style="color:black">Locality</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:7.68pt; text-align:left"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="font-size:12px">&bull;<span style="color:black">Exploit trade-offs</span></span></span></div>\r\n', '<span style="color:null"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="font-size:12px"><strong>1. Multihop</strong> <strong>wireless communication </strong>: A direct communication between a sender and a receiver is possible using prohibitively high transmission power. The use of intermediate nodes as relays can reduce the total required power.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; text-align:justify"><span style="color:null"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="font-size:12px"><strong>2. Energy-efficient operation </strong>To support long lifetimes, energy-efficient operation is a key technique.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; text-align:justify"><span style="color:null"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="font-size:12px"><strong>3. Auto-configuration:</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:12.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:null"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="font-size:12px">&bull;A WSN will have to configure most of its operational parameters autonomously, independent of external configuration &ndash; </span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:12.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:null"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="font-size:12px">&bull;the sheer number of nodes and simplified deployment will require that capability in most applications. </span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:12.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:null"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="font-size:12px">&bull;As an example, nodes should be able to determine their geographical positions only using other nodes of the network &ndash; so-called &ldquo;self-location&rdquo;. </span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:12.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:null"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="font-size:12px">&bull;Also, the network should be able to tolerate failing nodes (because of a depleted battery, for example) or to integrate new nodes (because of incremental deployment after failure, for example).</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:12.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:null"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="font-size:12px">4.&nbsp;</span></span></span><strong style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,Times,serif; font-size:12px; text-align:left">Collaboration and in-network processing</strong></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:12.0pt; text-align:justify">\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.24pt; text-align:left"><span style="color:null"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="font-size:12px">&bull;In some applications, <u>a single sensor is not able to decide </u>whether an event has happened but several sensors have to <u>collaborate to detect an event</u> and only the joint data of many sensors provides enough information. </span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.24pt; text-align:left"><span style="color:null"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="font-size:12px">&bull;Information is processed in the network itself in various forms to achieve this collaboration, as opposed to having every node transmit all data to an external network and process it &ldquo;at the edge&rdquo; of the network.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.24pt; text-align:left"><span style="color:null"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="font-size:12px">&bull;An example is to determine the <u>highest or the average temperature within an area</u> and to report that value to a sink. </span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.24pt; text-align:left"><span style="color:null"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="font-size:12px">&bull;To solve such tasks efficiently, readings from individual sensors can be <u><em>aggregated</em></u> as they propagate through the network, reducing the amount of data to be transmitted and hence improving the energy efficiency. How to perform such aggregation is an open question.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:6.24pt; text-align:left">\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; text-align:justify"><span style="color:null"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="font-size:12px"><strong>5. Data centric </strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:12.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:null"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="font-size:12px">&bull;In a WSN, where nodes are typically deployed redundantly to protect against node failures or to compensate for the low quality of a single node&rsquo;s actual sensing equipment, the identity of the particular node supplying data becomes irrelevant.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:12.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:null"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="font-size:12px">&bull;An example for such a data-centric interaction would be to request the average temperature in a given location area, as opposed to requiring temperature readings from individual nodes. Such a data-centric paradigm can also be used to set conditions for alerts or events (&ldquo;raise an alarm if temperature exceeds a threshold&rdquo;)</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:12.0pt; text-align:justify">\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; text-align:justify"><span style="color:null"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="font-size:12px"><strong>6. Locality </strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:12.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:null"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="font-size:12px">&bull;<strong>T</strong>he principle of locality will have to ensure, in particular, scalability. </span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:12.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:null"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="font-size:12px">&bull;Nodes, which are very limited in resources like memory, should attempt to limit the state that they accumulate during protocol processing to only information about their direct neighbors. </span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:12.0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:null"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="font-size:12px">&bull;It will allow the network to scale to large numbers of nodes without having to rely on powerful processing at each single node.</span></span></span></div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n', '', '', 'IA 2'),
('18EC741', '', 'Module 4', 'CO  4', 'KL 3', 10, '<span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="font-size:10px">With neat block diagram explain the Single node architecture of a wireless sensor network&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 10M</span></span></p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 3111, '', '<span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="color:black"><strong>Single-Node Architecture Hardware components</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0in; text-align:left"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="font-size:12px"><span style="color:black"><strong>Sensor node hardware overview</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:left"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="font-size:12px">&bull;<span style="color:black"><strong>Controller </strong>A controller to process all the relevant data, capable of executing arbitrary code.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:left"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="font-size:12px">&bull;<span style="color:black"><strong>Memory </strong>Some memory to store programs and intermediate data; usually, different types of memory are used for programs and data.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:left"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="font-size:12px">&bull;<span style="color:black"><strong>Sensors and actuators </strong>The actual interface to the physical world: devices that can observe or control physical parameters of the environment.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:left"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="font-size:12px">&bull;<span style="color:black"><strong>Communication </strong>Turning nodes into a network requires a device for sending and receiving information over a wireless channel.</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:left"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif"><span style="font-size:12px">&bull;<span style="color:black"><strong>Power supply </strong>As usually no tethered power supply is available, some form of batteries are necessary to provide energy. Sometimes, some form of recharging by obtaining energy from the environment is available as well (e.g. solar cells).</span></span></span></div>\r\n\r\n<div style="margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:.38in; margin-top:5.76pt; text-align:left">&nbsp;</div>\r\n', '', '', 'IA 2'),
