('18EC741', '', 'Module 4', 'CO  4', 'KL 3', 10, '<span style="font-size:10.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Define a Sensor &amp; Actuators. Briefly explain the three classifications of Sensors with suitable examples&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;10M</span></span></p>\r\n', 'Y', '', '', '', '', '', '', 0, 0, 3771, '<span style="font-size:10px"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif">Sensors - 2M</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="font-size:10px"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif">Actuators - 2M</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="font-size:10px"><span style="font-family:Times New Roman,Times,serif">Three classifications of Sensors - 6M&nbsp;</span></span></p>\r\n', '<span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="font-family:Carlito,&quot;sans-serif&quot;"><strong><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;">Sensors</span></span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0cm; margin-right:0cm; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Carlito,&quot;sans-serif&quot;"><span style="font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;">Sensors can be roughly categorized into three categories :</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0cm; margin-right:0cm; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Carlito,&quot;sans-serif&quot;"><strong><span style="font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;">Passive, omnidirectional sensors </span></strong><span style="font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;">These sensors can measure a physical quantity at the point of the sensor node without actually manipulating the environment by active probing &ndash; in this sense, they are passive. Moreover, some of these sensors actually are self-powered in the sense that they obtain the energy they need from the environment &ndash; energy is only needed to amplify their analog signal. There is no notion of &ldquo;direction&rdquo; involved in these measurements. Typical examples for such sensors include thermometer, light sensors, vibration, microphones, humidity, mechanical stress or tension in materials, chemical sensors sensitive for given substances, smoke detectors, air pressure, and so on.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style="margin-left:0cm; margin-right:0cm; text-align:justify"><span style="font-size:12pt"><span style="font-family:Carlito,&quot;sans-serif&quot;"><strong><span style="font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;">Passive, narrow-beam sensors </span></strong><span style="font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;">These sensors are passive as well, but have a well-defined notion of direction of measurement. A typical example is a camera, which can &ldquo;take measurements&rdquo; in a given direction, but has to be rotated if need be.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><span style="font-size:11.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;">Active sensors </span></span></strong><span style="font-size:11.0pt"><span style="font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;">This last group of sensors actively probes the environment, for example, a sonar or radar sensor or some types of seismic sensors, which generate shock waves by small explosions. These are quite specific &ndash; triggering an explosion is certainly not a lightly under- taken action &ndash; and require quite special attention.</span></span></p>\r\n', '', '', '3IA');
